{[%evp 0,21,19,29,23,-12,21,-14,0,-26,45,-12,42,-5,11,27,27,0,46,25,11,31,33,33]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 {We have the so-called ''reversed Gruenfeld. In this Chapter, we will ensure that White's extra tempo (compared to Grunfeld's) is a deal breaker in many rare variations.} Qb6 $6 {4.Qb3 or 4.Qf3 Bg7 5.Qb3 is among White's main attempts to fight for an advantage in Grunfeld. However, this approach definitely cannot be recommended with White's bishop on g2 - Black delays his development for too long.} (4... g6 $6 {This way of development is dubious:} 5. c4 {The most energetic, although 5.dxc5!? also deserving of attention.} Bg7 (5... dxc4 {runs into} 6. d5 Nb4 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. O-O Nf6 9. Ne5 O-O 10. Nxc4 $16 {White has a big space advantage, while the b4 is poor. Leonard,A -Perry,B ICCF email 2016}) 6. cxd5 Nxd4 {This was Yeletsky,I - Aradhya,G Chess.com INT 2022 Here I mostly like the simple} 7. Nc3 $146 Bg4 8. Nd2 $1 {Not allowing Black to damage the pawn chain with ...Nxf3.} Nf6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nb3 {Liquidating the most active piece of the opponent.} Nxb3 11. Qxb3 $36 {The strong d5-pawn and superior piece coordination offer White a clear advantage.}) ({The same can be said about} 4... c4 $6 {Black wastes too much time at the begining.} 5. O-O Nf6 6. b3 cxb3 7. axb3 Bf5 8. Ba3 $36 {White has a serious development advantage, and c2-c4 will follow soon.}) (4... Bg4 5. c4 $1 {As usual, this typical break is very effective. Especially after the desertion of light-squared of Black's queenside.} e6 ({After} 5... Bxf3 6. Bxf3 Nxd4 7. Bxd5 $16 {The un opposite d5 is too strong. Velickovic,Z - Mika,J Hungary 2002}) 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. Bg5 $1 {Black has an unfavorable version of Tarrasch with a premature Bc8-g4. As a result, the d5-pawn is especially vulnerable.} Be7 9. dxc5 d4 10. Bxf6 $1 {A well-timed exchange. White secures e4 for his knight.} Bxf6 11. Ne4 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. b4 $16 {Black didn't have compensation for a pawn in Werner,D - Ostojic,P Hamburg 1981}) (4... Bf5 5. O-O e6 6. c4 {We have a standard situation when extra tempo drastically changes the valuation, compared to Grunfeld with 4.Bf4.} dxc4 7. Qa4 Qa5 8. Qxc4 Qb4 9. Qxb4 Nxb4 10. Na3 $36 {White's lead in development prevails. Cusnariov,N - Starostits,I Berlin 2017}) (4... Nf6 {This move mostly transposes to positions covered in other Chapters, but there are some independent cases.} 5. O-O Bg4 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. c4 {is analyzed in another Chapter.}) ({Too risky is} 5... Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxc5 7. Be3 Qd6 8. c4 dxc4 9. Nbd2 $36 {Vastrukhin,O - Yakovlev,E Novorossiysk 2021}) 6. c4 Bxf3 7. Bxf3 cxd4 (7... Nxd4 8. Bg2 e6 {was seen in dozen of games. Here I suggest} 9. cxd5 $5 $146 Nxd5 10. Nc3 {White manages to regain the pawn in a favorable situation.} Be7 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. b4 $1 {It makes sense to open more files} O-O 13. bxc5 Bxc5 14. Bb2 Ne6 15. Qxd5 $14 {White has a stable advantage due to his powerful bishops.}) 8. Qb3 {A double attack.} e6 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Qxb7 Qc8 11. Qxc8+ Rxc8 12. Nd2 $14 {White has the better endgame because of strong Bf3. Ortiz,M - Jacewicz,G LSS email 2013}) 5. c4 $1 $146 {This most aggressive reaction is a novelty. White claims the main drawback of the last move - it diminishes Black's control of d5!} dxc4 ({After} 5... Nxd4 6. cxd5 Nxf3+ 7. Bxf3 $16 {Black struggles to complete development, while the d5-pawn makes the queenside very cramped.}) 6. dxc5 Qxc5 7. Be3 {White gains an important tempo by attacking the queen.} Qb4+ ({Hardly better is} 7... Qa5+ 8. Nbd2 Nf6 9. O-O $36) 8. Bd2 Qb6 ({The ''greedy''} 8... Qxb2 $2 9. Nc3 Qb6 10. Nd5 Qd8 11. Bf4 {leads to fatal consequences for Black.}) 9. O-O e5 10. Qa4 Bd7 11. Qxc4 $14 {White's pieces are mobilized much better, and the Bg2 plays an important role.} *

