{[%evp 0,27,29,16,25,-22,6,8,-9,-15,-5,-5,6,12,45,20,14,18,28,16,18,-2,1,-3,29,28,21,21,61,37]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 e6 5. O-O cxd4 6. Nxd4 Bc5 {This way of handling the position is common on the GM's level. Black intends to enter the ''Tarrasch'' paths after the Nd4 leaves.} (6... Nf6 7. c4 Bc5 8. Nb3 Bb6 {is another common moves order.}) ({Another way of attacking the centralized knight is} 6... Qb6 {, but the vulnerability of Qb6 makes White's development advantage more significant.} 7. Nxc6 {It makes sense to exchange the only developed piece of the opponent.} bxc6 8. c4 Nf6 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nc3 {Everything is ready for a thematic e2-e4 advance.} Bb7 ({After} 10... Be7 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nd5 13. Nc3 $16 {Black loses a pawn because of dangerous pin.}) 11. Be3 Qa6 12. a4 $1 {White finds an effective way to activate his knight and pose Black concrete problems.} Bc6 {Preventing ..Nb5, but now Black faces another problem.} 13. Qd4 $1 Be7 14. b4 $16 {The q-side pawns look threatening. Pavlenko,B - Kamenov,V Albena 2016}) 7. Nb3 (7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. c4 Nf6 9. Qc2 {is a common alternative, but after} Qe7 $1 {Black seems to be able to solve his problems as the critical line} 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. b4 Bd4 {offers White no advantage.}) 7... Bb6 8. c4 Nf6 ({Dubious is} 8... dxc4 $6 9. Qxd8+ Bxd8 10. N3d2 Na5 11. Na3 c3 12. bxc3 Bd7 13. Nac4 $16 {Black got under strong pressure a-la Catalan in Vastrukhin,O - Ponkratov,P Anapa 2021}) ({An equal alternative is} 8... Nge7 $5 9. Nc3 O-O ({After} 9... d4 10. c5 dxc3 11. cxb6 Qxb6 12. bxc3 $14 {The bishop pair prevails. Wojtkiewicz,A - Urban,K Katowice 1995}) 10. cxd5 Nxd5 ({In case of} 10... exd5 11. Na4 $1 Bc7 12. Be3 $14 {White sets up blockade on d4, and Black starts to suffer from having an isolani.}) 11. Na4 $1 {I find this move more promising} ({than} 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Qxd5 Bg4 {when Black has an excellent piece play and decent compensation for a pawn.}) 11... Bc7 12. Bd2 Qe7 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Wang,H - Gustafsson,J Pattaya 2015 Here I suggest:} 13. Qc2 $146 {White connects his rooks and prevents the consolidating ...b7-b6} Rd8 14. Rfd1 Be5 15. Nc3 $14 {Black still struggles to develop his light-squared bishop.}) 9. Nc3 O-O ({Dubious is} 9... d4 $6 10. Nb5 a6 ({After} 10... e5 11. c5 Bc7 12. Bg5 Bb8 13. e3 $16 {Black is unable to cover his central pawn.}) 11. Bxc6+ $1 {White doesn't fear ghosts! The central pawn is worth it.} bxc6 12. N5xd4 e5 {This was Lasanta Rica,C - Jovancevic,J Barcelona 2022 In my opinion, White should have neutralized any counterplay of an opponent by means of} 13. c5 $1 $146 Bxc5 14. Nxc5 exd4 15. e4 O-O 16. Bf4 $16 {Black has no compensation for his poor pawn structure.}) ({Worse is also} 9... dxc4 10. Nd2 {The Catalan Bg2 is getting much more powerful.} Ne5 ({In the event of} 10... Na5 11. b4 $1 cxb3 12. Ba3 $40 {Black is nearly lost as his king will most likely stay in the center till the end of the game.}) 11. b3 $1 Qe7 (11... cxb3 12. Ba3 {is bad, as after 10...Na5.}) 12. Na4 $1 Bc7 (12... Bd4 $2 {The following line illustrates Black's issues with development:} 13. Nxc4 Bxa1 14. Ba3 {is fatal for Black.}) 13. Nxc4 Nxc4 14. bxc4 O-O 15. Qb3 $16 {Black had serious problems developing queenside pieces. Maetzig,R - Wittenberg,G GER email 2017}) 10. Bg5 {The nasty pin forces Black to clear the situation in the center.} dxc4 11. Nd2 h6 ({White keeps some pressure also after} 11... Bd4 $5 12. Nxc4 h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Ne4 $14) 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Nxc4 Bc7 14. Nb5 $14 {White has a dream version of Catalan. Enev,Z - Valiente,J LSS email 2019} *

