{[%evp 0,49,25,25,25,-20,-1,-1,-14,-26,6,12,6,4,16,16,11,6,18,-4,17,20,-2,-23,28,51,36,10,6,-7,-12,31,0,0,0,0,0,11,16,-8,8,25,73,79,84,66,66,42,41,36,20,24]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 {Like in Grunfeld, Black is relying on his strong pawn center. However, the presence of Bg2 makes it much more vulnerable.} 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 Nf6 {This important theoretical position might be raised with different move orders.} ({Dubious is} 7... Bb4+ $6 8. Nc3 d4 {This standard pawn sacrifice was seen in Hillarp Persson,T - Goloshchapov,A Ohrid 2001} ({After} 8... Ne7 9. cxd5 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 cxd5 11. O-O Be6 12. c4 $16 {Black struggle to castle, when his central pawns are very vulnerable. Sulava,N - Jokic,M Rijeka 2008}) {White has few ways to claim the misplaced Bb4, but I mostly like} 9. a3 $5 $146 Ba5 10. Bxc6+ Bd7 11. Qa4 {Black isn't in time to capture on c3 because his Ba5 is hanging again. Also, White can always unpin the Nc3 with b2-b4.} Nf6 ({Equally bad is} 11... Bxc6 12. Qxc6+ Kf8 13. b4 $16) 12. Bxd7+ Nxd7 13. b4 dxc3 14. bxa5 O-O 15. Qb4 $16 {The c3-pawn will fall soon. Black doesn't seem to have any compensation for his material losses.}) (7... Be6 {is another natural continuation. Such strong players as Duda, Savchenko, and others played it. By deviating from 7...Nf6, Black eliminates the pin of his knight.} 8. Nc3 {Increasing the pressure on d5.} Nf6 {After all, there is nothing better for Black.} ({After} 8... Bb4 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 Ne7 11. Ba3 $16 {The pressure of both bishops makes Black's position very difficult. Vulinovic,R - Petrovic,P Belgrade 2017}) 9. Bg5 Bb4 {The exchange on c3 will diminish White's control of d5.} (9... e4 {is a clear positional concession as it weakens d4} 10. Qa4 Bd7 11. O-O Be7 12. Rfd1 O-O 13. Qc2 $16 {Black's pawn center was about to collapse in Ladva,O - Narva,M Puhajarve 2016}) 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qa5 ({After} 11... O-O 12. cxd5 Bxd5 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Qa4 $14 {Black suffers from damaged pawn structure on the queenside, so his king gets under permanent pressure. Reuter,M-Mueller,H DESC email 2016}) 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. c4 Rd8 {After the natural play by both sides, the critical position was reached. Here I suggest} 14. Rb1 $5 $146 ({Instead,} 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Bxd5 Rxd5 {leaves White with a minimal advantage because of limited material balance. Rakhmanov,A - Savchenko,B Khanty-Mansiysk 2016}) 14... O-O ({Riskier is} 14... dxc4 15. Bc6+ Kf8 16. Rb8 $1 {A nice tactical resource. Black fails to connect his rooks.} Ke7 17. Rb7+ Kf8 18. Qb1 h6 19. Be3 $36 {White has a powerful initiative because of poor Rh8 and exposed Kf8.}) 15. Rb5 {The rook's activation allows White to destroy the pawn center.} Qxa2 16. cxd5 Bg4 17. Re1 Qc4 18. Ra5 $36 {The strong d5-pawn is supported by the bishop pair.}) 8. O-O ({Another common move is} 8. Nc3 {, but it allows} d4 $5 9. Bxc6+ Bd7 10. Bxa8 Qxa8 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. cxd5 Qxd5 13. f3 Bc5 {Black got decent compensation for an exchange in Svane,R - Caruana,F Almaty 2022}) 8... Be6 {The most reasonable choice - Black develops his bishop and strengthens d5.} ({In case of} 8... Be7 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nc3 Be6 11. Bg5 {Black is practically forced to unblock the h1-a8 diagonal.} d4 ({After} 11... e4 12. Qa4+ Qd7 13. Qxd7+ Nxd7 14. Be3 $14 {White's structural superiority in undenieble.}) 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 (12... gxf6 13. Nb5 Rb8 14. Nxa7 Rxb2 {was seen in Brodowski,P - Bartel,M Szklarska Poreba 2013 White should have continued} 15. a4 $1 $146 Bd5 16. Rc1 O-O 17. Nc6 Bxc6 18. Rxc6 $16 {The bishops of opposite color favor White, who has excellent attacking prospects.}) 13. Nb5 $1 {A precise move.} Rb8 14. Nxa7 Rxb2 $146 {I find this move the most challenging.} ({After} 14... Qb6 15. Qa4+ Bd7 16. Bc6 $16 {Black is left with no compensation for a pawn. Venkataramanan,T - Jackson,E Leamington Spa 2021}) 15. Qc1 $1 {A decent tactical resource. The Ke8 is stuck in the center, so Black should be careful.} Qb6 (15... Rxe2 16. Qc5 e4 17. Nb5 $18 {is crushing.}) 16. a4 O-O 17. a5 $16 {Black finds hard times with stopping the a-passer.}) ({The prophylactic} 8... h6 {feels to slow, although h6 was successfully employed by Vladimir Kramnik in Gruenfeld.} 9. Nc3 Be6 10. Qa4 Bd7 ({After} 10... Qd7 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Qxd7+ Kxd7 13. Rd1 {the pinned d5-pawn causes Black serious problems.}) 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Qa6 Be6 13. Rd1 $36 {This position was tested in 4 games. It looks neutralizing White's initiative is a hard task. Black only scored half a point!}) (8... Rb8 {In analogy with Grunfeld, Black steps out of pin along the h1-a8 diagonal and keeps an eye on the b2-pawn. On the downside, the other pieces remain undeveloped.} 9. Bg5 $1 {Still, White doesn't fear ghosts!} Be7 (9... Rxb2 {, as in Baliasnyj,T - Navara,D Antalya 2017 is naturally met by} 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Nc3 d4 12. Nd5 $18 {White's development advantage is too big. Black has to evade a nasty threat of 13.Qa4+.}) 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Bxd5 O-O ({Also after} 12... Rxb2 13. Qa4+ Bd7 14. Qxa7 e4 15. Rd1 O-O 16. Na3 $14 {White manages to complete development and maintain the extra pawn. Hoeppenstein,M-Hlavacek,L DESC email 2014}) 13. Bb3 $1 {White can do without retreating the bishop on g2.} Bh3 14. Re1 e4 15. Qxd8 {Of course, the queen's trade makes White's position safer.} Rfxd8 16. Nc3 Re8 17. Red1 $14 {Black's compensation seems insufficient despite the strong bishops. Emrich,E - Grube,A GER email 2014}) 9. Qa4 (9. Nc3 Rc8 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Qa4+ Qd7 {might lead to the same position.}) 9... Qd7 {The most natural response.} ({Artificial is} 9... Bd7 10. Bg5 Be7 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Qa3 $36 {Black cannot castle, and the d5-pawn is very vulnerable.}) 10. Nc3 Rc8 ({Hardly can be recommended} 10... Rb8 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Qxd7+ Kxd7 13. Rd1 d4 14. e3 Bc5 15. Na4 $16 {Black loses his central pawn for free. Nakamura,H - Anand,V Stavanger 2017}) 11. cxd5 {Black was ready to advance his d-pawn, so this is practically forced.} cxd5 12. Qxd7+ Kxd7 13. Rd1 Bc5 {An interesting pawn sacrifice. Black mobilizes all his forces and connects the rooks.} ({Worse is} 13... d4 $2 14. e3 Bc5 15. Na4 $18) 14. Na4 $1 {In my opinion, only this strong move might pose Black any problems.} (14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Bxd5 16. Rxd5+ Ke6 17. Rd2 Rhd8 {was tested in dozens of games, and it looks like the activity of rooks offers him decent compensation for a pawn.}) 14... Be7 ({There are few possible alternatives at Black's disposal:} 14... h6 15. Nxc5+ Rxc5 16. f4 $1 {White takes control over the dark squares at the cost of temporarily blocking the Bg2.} e4 17. h3 Rc2 ({Also after} 17... h5 18. Be3 Rc2 19. Bxa7 Rxb2 20. Bd4 Rxe2 21. a4 {the strong a-passer puts Black in big danger.}) 18. g4 Ke7 {Black has to vacate d7 for his bishop.} 19. Be3 Rhc8 ({Worse is} 19... Rxe2 20. Bc5+ Ke8 21. Bxa7 Rxb2 22. Bd4 $16) 20. Bxa7 Rxe2 21. a4 $1 Rxb2 22. Bd4 Rbc2 23. a5 $14 {The strong passer is supported by bishops, while Black's extra pawn doesn't tell. Jamka Pietron,B-Sileika,A ICCF email 2016}) (14... Bd6 15. Bg5 Rc4 ({After} 15... Rc2 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Bxd5 Rxe2 18. Be4 $1 $18 {the Re2 will be trapped. Of course, the Be4 is intouchable in view of Nc5+.}) 16. b3 Rc2 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Bxd5 f5 {Black relies on his active Rc2, but it isn't enough.} 19. Rac1 Rhc8 20. Bc4 $14 {White successfully consolidated and maintained the extra pawn in Ganguly,S - Li,D China 2019}) 15. Bg5 Ng8 {A tricky move - by exchanging the dark-squared bishop, Black secures the d5-pawn.} ({In case of} 15... Rhd8 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Bxd5 Ke7 {White should play accurately to neutralize the activity of Black's rooks.} 18. Bxe6 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Kxe6 {We have been following the game Banusz,T - Hracek,Z Porec 2022 In my opinion, White should have limited Black's active possibilities with} 20. e4 $146 Be7 (20... Rc4 21. b3 Rc2 22. Rd5 Rxa2 23. Ra5 $16) 21. Rd3 Rc4 22. Nc3 Bb4 23. f3 $14 {It will be a game for two results only.}) 16. h4 Bxg5 ({After} 16... d4 17. Bd2 $1 {White is ready for a break in the center with e2-e3.} Nh6 {This position occurred in Kagansky,M - Gray,G ICCF email 2018 Here, my recommendation is} 18. b4 $1 $146 Rc7 (18... Nf5 19. e4 Nh6 20. Bf1 $14 {The Nh6 is out of play.}) 19. b5 Ba3 20. Bc6+ Ke7 21. Ba5 $14 {White has excellent prospects on the queenside.}) 17. hxg5 Ne7 18. Nc3 Rc5 {The only way of defending the d5-pawn.} 19. Rd2 Rd8 {The optimal play by both sides led to this position in Meskovs,N - Khenkin,I Kiel 2021 White could have forced favorable simplifications by means of} 20. Bxd5 $146 Nxd5 21. e4 Kc6 22. exd5+ Bxd5 23. Rad1 Rd7 {Black manages to step out of the pin, but it doesn't solve all the issues.} 24. f3 Be6 25. Kf2 $14 {White has a slight advantage due to the more active rook and pawns majority on the queenside.} *

