{[%evp 0,35,25,22,19,-5,-1,-10,15,-10,19,-3,45,-1,-10,30,20,24,24,24,3,15,33,4,19,17,8,18,30,-2,42,-20,-15,-13,-39,-22,-3,-10]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. O-O g6 {A very solid setup. Black plays a reversed Gruenfeld with g2-g3.} 5. c4 {I find this most promising. Now Black has to make an important decision.} ({Another common move is} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 {it leads to reversed Grunfeld with g3. White's extra tempo is viable, but it hardly is possible to pose serious Black problems in this line.}) 5... Bg7 {The most common response by far.} (5... dxc4 {allows White to regain the pawn in favorable redaction:} 6. Qa4+ Nbd7 (6... Bd7 7. Qxc4 Qb6 {, as in So,W - Anand,V Leon 2017 runs into} 8. Ng5 $1 $146 e6 9. Qc3 Be7 10. Ne4 {The effect of pinned Ng6 is fatal for Black.}) 7. Qxc4 Bg7 8. d4 {The most energetic. White claims the misplaced Nd7 and opens the d-file.} cxd4 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. Rd1 Qb6 11. Nc3 $16 {Black got under standard pressure a-la Catalan in Nichols,S - Steenlandt,A ICCF email 2011}) ({Insufficient for equality is also} 5... Nc6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 cxd4 ({After} 7... Bg7 8. e4 Nc7 9. d5 Nd4 10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. Na3 $14 {White has the better piece coordination, and the d4 is somewhat unsafe.}) 8. Nxd4 Bg7 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. e4 Nb4 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Nc3 $14 {Black suffers from weak c6-pawn. Byway,P - Ward,J Hinckley Island 2009}) 6. Qa4+ $5 {A tricky idea. Black is invited to show his cards when any move covering the king from check has drawbacks.} Nc6 {The most common move.} ({After} 6... Qd7 7. Qxd7+ Nbxd7 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nc3 {Black has a slightly inferior endgame in view of misplaced Nd7.} N7b6 10. a4 $1 {The most energetic. White is aiming to extend his initiative on the queenside.} Nxc3 {This was Akesson,R - Afek,Y Vlissingen 2008} ({After} 10... a5 11. Ng5 Nb4 12. d3 O-O 13. Be3 {Black also suffers from weak queenside pawns.}) {Now my new idea is} 11. dxc3 $5 $146 a5 12. Nd2 Ra7 13. Nb3 $14 {White has a stable advantage due to his strong Bg2.}) ({Another solid option is} 6... Bd7 7. Qb3 dxc4 8. Qxc4 Qb6 9. Ne5 {White may benefit from exchanging the Bd7.} Be6 10. Qa4+ Nbd7 11. d3 O-O 12. Nc4 Qc7 {The optimal play led to this position in Giri,A - Anand,V Leuven 2017 In my opinion, White could have tried to set up some problems with} 13. Nc3 $146 Nb6 14. Qa5 Nfd5 15. Bxd5 $1 {A well-timed exchange. White can afford to weaken his king.} Bxc3 16. bxc3 Nxd5 17. Qxc7 Nxc7 18. Na3 b6 19. Bf4 Nd5 20. Bd2 $14 {Although there are bishops of different colors on the board, this endgame is somewhat uncomfortable for Black because he has no counterplay, while White has decent prospects on the queenside. The main strategic idea is to play c3-c4 and a3-a4 and isolate the b6-pawn.}) (6... Nbd7 $6 {was played by three strong players, but it is dubious.} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nc3 N5b6 9. Qc2 O-O 10. d3 Nf6 11. Rd1 $36 {White has a more harmonious setup, and it is hard to neutralize the powerful Bg2. Cvitan,O - Fressinet,L Solin/Split 2000}) 7. Ne5 $1 {Undoubtedly, this is the most interesting choice. White is aiming to damage the opponent's pawn structure.} Qd6 ({Another natural possibility is} 7... Bd7 8. Nxd7 Qxd7 {, and now I suggest the flexible} 9. d3 $5 $146 ({In case of} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nc3 e6 11. Qc4 {Eljanov,P - Erigaisi,A Chess.com INT 2020 Black can ignore White's threat with} O-O $1 $146 12. Nxd5 (12. Qxc5 Nd4 13. Nxd5 Nxe2+ 14. Kh1 exd5 $11) 12... exd5 13. Qxc5 (13. Qxd5 Qe7 $44) 13... Nd4 14. e3 Ne2+ 15. Kh1 d4 $44 {Black seems to have reasonable compensation as all his pieces are much more active.}) 9... O-O ({The attempt to simplify the matters with} 9... Nd4 10. Qxd7+ Nxd7 {doesn't fully solve Black's strategic issues:} 11. Nc3 dxc4 12. dxc4 O-O-O 13. Rb1 Ne5 14. b3 $14) ({The same can be said about} 9... dxc4 10. dxc4 O-O 11. Nc3 $14) 10. Nc3 {White is interested in prolonging the diagonal for Bg2.} d4 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Qd6 13. a3 $14 {In this complex middlegame, White's chances are superior due to his strong, un opposite light-squared bishop.}) ({I examned also} 7... O-O $146 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Qxc6 Bg4 10. Re1 Rc8 11. Qa6 {Perhaps, Black doesn't have much for a pawn because White has no weaknesses, and the queenside pieces should be developed soon.}) 8. cxd5 (8. Nxc6 Bd7 $1 9. cxd5 Nxd5 {Black has nothing to worry about.}) 8... Nxd5 9. Nc4 Qd8 ({Another retreat is more artificial:} 9... Qe6 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. dxc3 O-O 12. Nb6 $1 {White takes advantage of Black's disconnected rooks.} axb6 13. Qxa8 Qxe2 14. Qa4 {Black didn't have sufficient compensation for an exchange in Speelman,J - Ribli,Z Germany 2000}) 10. Nc3 e6 ({Worth attention is} 10... Nb6 $5 11. Bxc6+ ({After} 11. Nxb6 Qxb6 12. Nd5 Qd8 13. Qa3 Be6 14. Qxc5 Rc8 $44 {Black has full compensation for a pawn due to superior development.}) 11... bxc6 12. Nxb6 $146 (12. Qxc6+ Bd7 13. Qe4 Bf5 {took place in 1 correspondence game. I think the strong bishops provide decent Black play for a pawn.}) 12... Qxb6 13. Nd5 {White transfers his knight on e3 to strengthen control of c4.} Qb7 14. d3 Bd7 (14... O-O {runs into} 15. Qxc6 Rd8 16. Qxb7 Bxb7 17. Ne3 $14) 15. Ne3 O-O 16. Qc2 Bd4 17. Rb1 {Black may have sufficient compensation for his structural drawbacks, but precise play is required.}) 11. Ne3 O-O {The most challenging move. Black sacrifices the pawn to involve all the remaining pieces.} ({After} 11... Nxe3 $2 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. dxe3 O-O 14. e4 $16 {the c8 is passive, and the c-pawns are very vulnerable.}) 12. Nexd5 exd5 13. Nxd5 Re8 {This important position occurred in Rapport,R - Vidit,S Danzhou 2019 Here I like the following new conception:} 14. e4 $5 $146 {White weakens d4 to maintain his centralized knight.} Bg4 (14... Bd7 {yields White time for consolidating:} 15. Qd1 Be6 16. d3 Qd7 17. Be3 b6 ({After} 17... Bxb2 18. Rb1 Bg7 19. Bxc5 $14 {White's central pawns are quite strong.}) 18. Rb1 Bxd5 19. exd5 Nb4 20. Qb3 $14 {The bishop pair also plays an important role.}) 15. d3 Be2 16. Be3 $1 {White bravely sacrifices the exchange.} Bxf1 17. Rxf1 Qd6 18. f4 $44 {This position offers interesting play for both sides, but I slightly prefer White, who can potentially extend in the center.} *

