{[%evp 0,31,28,19,19,-1,-10,-10,-1,-2,19,44,37,-23,-18,-17,0,-29,6,-2,23,20,20,0,0,0,0,9,14,12,19,23,6,-18]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. O-O g6 5. c4 d4 {The most ambitious continuation. Black seizes lots of space and restricts White's minor pieces. On the other hand, the k-side fianchetto isn't always well combined with ...d5-d4.} 6. b4 {The most common and ambitious move. White reasonably challenges the pawn center at once to take advantage of superior development.} cxb4 {The most challenging reaction - after all, Black is up a pawn now.} ({In case of} 6... Bg7 7. bxc5 {Black struggles to regain the pawn in acceptable redaction.} Nfd7 ({In case of} 7... O-O 8. d3 Nc6 (8... Nfd7 9. Nbd2 Nxc5 {transposes to 7...0-0}) 9. Nbd2 Nd7 ({Hardly more attractive for Black is} 9... e5 10. Ng5 {The usual approach: White's knight is heading on d6, while the Bg2 is unblocked now.} Ne8 11. Nge4 f5 12. Nd6 Nxd6 13. cxd6 Qxd6 14. Qa4 $16 {White has a free initiative on the q-side. Obukhov,A - Vitiugov,N St Petersburg 2002}) 10. Nb3 {Black doesn't have much for a pawn. For instance,} e5 11. Ng5 (11. e3 $5 {also looks very promising for White.}) 11... Nf6 12. Rb1 Qe7 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 {Black is missing a pawn, while his queenside got under pressure because of the strong tandem of Be4 and Rb1. Fressinet,L - Svidler,P chess24.com INT 2021}) 8. d3 Nxc5 9. Nbd2 Nc6 (9... O-O 10. Nb3 Na4 (10... Nba6 11. Ba3 Nxb3 12. axb3 $16) 11. Nbxd4 Bxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 (12... Nc3 $2 13. Qd2 Qxd4 14. Bb2 $18) 13. Bh6 Nc5 14. Bxf8 Kxf8 15. e3 Qf6 16. d4 $36) 10. Ba3) 7. Qa4+ (7. a3 $5 {offers a perfect White version of Volga gambit. However, such early pawn sacrifice isn't to everyone's taste.}) 7... Qd7 ({Riskier is} 7... Bd7 8. Qxb4 Nc6 {Almasi,Z - Esserman,M Reykjavik 2017 White shouldn't fear ghosts and grab the pawn:} 9. Qxb7 $1 $146 Rb8 10. Qa6 Bg7 {The most consistent.} ({After} 10... e5 11. Ba3 Rb6 ({Or} 11... e4 12. Ng5 Rb6 13. Qa4 Nb4 14. Qd1 $16) 12. Qa4 Nb4 13. Qd1 Qc7 14. d3 $14 {Black's initiative practically comes to an end.}) 11. d3 Nb4 {Black should act actively to convert his slight development advantage into something concrete.} 12. Qxa7 Nc2 13. Na3 Nxa1 ({Worse is} 13... Ra8 $2 14. Qxa8 Qxa8 15. Nxc2 {White has too much for a queen.}) 14. Qxd4 O-O ({After} 14... Nh5 15. Ne5 O-O 16. Qxa1 Qa5 17. f4 $16 {White also successfully consolidates and maintains his material advantage.}) 15. Qxa1 Ne4 16. Nd4 $1 {White Bravle pins his knight - Black cannot take advantage of somewhat unstable Nd4 as his knight is hanging.} Bh3 17. Be3 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 $16) 8. Qxb4 Nc6 {This position occurred in Lonnee,G - Kanios,M ICCF email 2018 I think White's most promising way to retreat the queen is} 9. Qb5 $1 $146 {Provoking ...a7-a6 and keeping an eye on e5.} Bg7 ({After} 9... a6 10. Qb6 Bg7 11. d3 O-O 12. a4 $14 {Black's queenside setup is crumped.}) 10. d3 O-O 11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. Qxe5 Ng4 13. Qc5 b6 (13... Qe6 14. h3 Nf6 15. Re1 $14 {Black still has to solve his issues with developing the q-side pieces.}) 14. Qc6 Qxc6 15. Bxc6 Rb8 16. a4 $14 {White has traditional structural superiority because Black doesn't have a clear plan, while ..a4-a5 will create weaknesses on the queenside.} *

