{[%evp 0,55,28,19,19,-10,-10,-14,-14,-5,-2,6,-1,-9,-13,-10,-17,-37,-26,-36,25,26,27,47,37,38,13,13,79,49,20,10,20,11,29,42,55,22,22,8,22,21,21,39,-7,23,5,16,0,-28,22,-19,-16,-28,-15,-6,-5,-14]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 Nf6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 {I believe this is the only way to fight for the initiative, although in most cases, we do not enter Catalan paths.} dxc4 {This is one of most researched Catalan tibias.} 7. Ne5 {The most aggressive choice.} ({The other common options are} 7. Qa4) ({and} 7. dxc5) 7... Bd7 (7... Nxe5 {is known as a dubious move:} 8. dxe5 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Nd5 ({Perhaps, even worse is} 9... Nd7 $6 10. Na3 Nxe5 11. Bf4 f6 12. Bxe5 fxe5 13. Nxc4 $16 {White had a huge positional advantage in a couple of games.}) 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Be7 12. Rb1 Rb8 13. Bc6+ Kf8 14. Bd7 {Garcia del Castillo,A-Illescas Lopez,A Malaga 2003}) 8. Nxc4 ({Another well-known way is} 8. Na3 cxd4 9. Naxc4 {, but the recent practice proves that after} Rc8 10. Qb3 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bd6 {White hardly achieves anything special.}) 8... cxd4 9. Bf4 Nd5 {The most common choice. By playing this, Black practically forces the further exchange of minor pieces.} 10. Nd6+ (10. Bd6 $2 Be7 {offers White no compensation for a pawn.}) 10... Bxd6 11. Bxd6 Nde7 {Definitely the safest. Black retreats his knight to block the a3-f8 diagonal and finally move his king from the danger zone.} ({The attempt to get a rid of Bd6 with} 11... Bc8 $6 12. Bc5 Nde7 {is artificial as Black is missing developed pieces.} 13. Nd2 O-O {This position occurred in Romanishin,O - Naiditsch,A Hungary 2009 White should have extended his initiative on the q-side by means of} 14. b4 $1 $146 Re8 ({Also after} 14... a6 15. a4 e5 16. b5 Na5 17. e3 $16 {White's bishops dominate over the knights.}) 15. b5 Ne5 16. Nb3 d3 17. a4 $36 {The activity of pieces clearly overwhelms Black's extra pawn.}) ({The materialistic} 11... Qb6 $6 12. Nd2 Qxb2 {Jayakumar,A - Norowitz,Y Philadelphia 2010 is bad in view of} 13. Rb1 $1 $146 Qxa2 14. Ra1 Qb2 15. Ba3 Qb5 16. Ne4 {, and the appearance of a knight on d6 will lead to fatal consequences.}) 12. Nd2 O-O {The most consistent.} ({Dubious is} 12... e5 $2 13. Qb3 Bc8 14. Qa3 {Black struggles to castle again.} f6 15. Rac1 Kf7 {Mirumian,V - Cernousek,L Plzen 2000 Now the energetic} 16. f4 $1 $146 exf4 17. Ne4 Re8 18. Bxf4 {offers White a stunning attack.}) 13. Qb3 Bc8 $1 {This move looks awkward, but Black should drive the Bd6 away as soon as possible.} ({Less precise is} 13... b6 {, although it was played by very strong players} 14. Rac1 Rc8 15. Ba3 $1 {White vacated d6 for his knight.} e5 ({After} 15... Re8 16. Ne4 Nf5 17. g4 $1 Nh4 18. Nd6 {Black doesn't have compensation for his material losses. Wellen,L - Zalascek,V LSS email 2012}) 16. Nc4 Be6 17. Qb5 {Black got under strong pressure in Seiler,W - Bartsch,C GER email 2010}) 14. Nc4 e5 ({Another natural measure is} 14... Re8 {unpinning the knight and preparing ...Nf5.} 15. Bc5 Nf5 16. Rac1 $5 {This natural move is a novelty. White builds pressure on the c-file and invites Black to show his cards.} ({After} 16. e4 dxe3 17. fxe3 Qg5 18. Ba3 e5 19. Nd6 Nxd6 20. Bxd6 Nd8 $1 {Black managed to successfully evade the threats. Eventually he won in Gelfand,B - Karpov,A Monte Carlo 1999}) 16... e5 {The only adequate way of involving the Bc8.} 17. e4 $1 {White temporarily blocks the Bg2 because Black wouldn't like to allow Nc4-d6.} dxe3 ({After} 17... Nfe7 18. Nd6 Rf8 19. f4 Be6 20. Qd3 b6 21. Ba3 $36 {the strong Nd6 dominates Black's pieces.}) 18. fxe3 Qg5 19. Be4 $36 {The threat of 20.Bxf5, followed by Nd6 makes Black's position rather uncomfortable.}) 15. Rac1 {White continues to play for a long-term initiative.} ({The attempt to fight for an advantage after regaining the pawn would fail:} 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Rfd1 Be6 17. Qb4 Re8 18. Nxe5 Nf5 19. Bc5 Bd5 {Black has the upper hand because White's king is very exposed.}) 15... Re8 16. Ba3 ({The materialistic} 16. Bxe5 Nf5 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Rfd1 Be6 {offers Black an excellent play.}) 16... Nf5 17. Be4 (17. e4 dxe3 18. fxe3 Qg5 19. Rf2 Ncd4 20. Qd1 Nc6) 17... Qf6 (17... Qc7 18. Qf3 g6 19. g4 Ng7 20. Nd6 $36 {White obtained a powerful initiative in Gelfand,B - Anand,V Leon 2022}) 18. Qf3 Rd8 {Perhaps, this is the safest choice. Black covers the key d6-spot.} ({The possible alternatives are:} 18... Be6 19. g4 Bxc4 ({In case of} 19... Nfe7 20. Qxf6 gxf6 21. Nd6 Reb8 22. f4 $36 {Black's king is in danger as practically all the pieces are located on the opposite side.}) 20. Rxc4 Nfe7 21. Qxf6 gxf6 22. Rfc1 $44 {The powerful bishops and superior pawn structure provide White full compensation for a pawn. I find White's play easier from a human point of view.}) (18... Rb8 19. g4 Nh4 20. Qxf6 gxf6 21. f3 $44 {Black's setup isn't optimal, and once the knight lands on d6, it might cause Black some concrete problems. Undoubtedly, White maintains decent compensation.}) 19. g4 {It is better to force the matters.} ({In case of} 19. b4 d3 $1 20. Bxd3 Be6 $132 {Black has excellent play due to the activity of his knights.}) 19... Nfe7 20. Qxf6 gxf6 21. Nd6 ({After} 21. f3 Be6 22. Nd6 Rab8 {White can regain the pawn, but it will only lead to equality:} 23. Nxb7 Rxb7 24. Bxe7 Rxe7 25. Rxc6 Kg7 $11) 21... Rb8 22. f4 $5 {White continues to play aggressively. Black is invited to grab another pawn.} Be6 ({Riskier is} 22... Bxg4 23. Kf2 Ng6 24. Rg1 {the opposition on the g-file looks too scary for a human player.}) 23. b3 Bd5 ({Also after} 23... Kg7 24. Rf2 Rd7 25. Bxc6 Nxc6 26. Ne4 $44 {White keeps interesting play for a pawn. The threat of 27.Nc5 is quite annoying.}) 24. g5 {This forces Black to play accurately.} fxg5 25. fxe5 Bxe4 26. Nxe4 Ng6 $1 {A precie move.} ({Weaker is} 26... Nd5 27. Bd6 Rbc8 28. Nxg5 $36) 27. Nxg5 Ncxe5 28. Rc7 {Black should be able to equalize, but White's play is easier from a practical point of view.} *

