{[%evp 0,56,28,19,14,-14,-14,6,6,-1,-1,-1,-1,18,-2,-17,-20,-36,-37,-33,-27,-53,-46,-50,-50,-50,-50,-76,-74,-83,-83,-83,-81,-81,-83,-55,-55,-67,-67,-62,-62,-225,-153,-153,-85,-128,0,-100,0,-59,-57,-54,-47,-21,-13,-28,-22,-18,5]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 Nf6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 dxc4 7. Ne5 Bd7 8. Nxc4 cxd4 9. Bf4 Be7 {This is Black's 2nd choice. As 9...Nd5, it invites interesting tactical complications.} ({Inferior is} 9... Rc8 $6 10. Nbd2 Be7 11. Nd6+ {This time, Black has to capture on d6 as the Rc8 is hanging.} Bxd6 12. Bxd6 e5 13. Rc1 $16 {Black was in big trouble as the Ke8 was stuck in the center, and the e5-pawn was about to fall. Xiong,J - Nogerbek,K Chess.com INT 2019}) 10. Nd6+ Kf8 $1 {Certainly the best. From now Black builds his counterplay on the vulnerability of Nd6.} ({After} 10... Bxd6 $2 11. Bxd6 Nd5 12. Nd2 Bc8 13. Bc5 Nde7 14. Qa4 $16 {it was very hard for Black to withstand the pressure of both bishops in Drexel,M - Stoer,A Bayern 2001}) 11. Nxb7 Qb6 12. Nd6 Qc5 ({The alternatives are less attractive for Black:} 12... Rd8 13. Nd2 Nd5 ({I also examined} 13... e5 $5 $146 14. N6c4 Qc7 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Rc1 $14 {The position remains complex, but White's play is easier from a human point of view: Black's pawn structure is damaged, and the opposition on the c-file is dangerous.}) 14. N6c4 Qc5 15. Ne5 Nxe5 {This position was reached in Bjerre,J - Moroni,L Germany 2021} ({After} 15... Nxf4 16. Nxd7+ Rxd7 17. gxf4 $36 {The h8 is out of play, so Black is in trouble.}) {White should have played} 16. Rc1 $1 $146 Qd6 17. Nc4 Qa6 (17... Nxc4 18. Bxd6 Nxd6 19. Qxd4 $16 {is very bad for Black, although he has three pieces for a queen - it will be hard to prevent the invasion of White's rooks and cover the weak pawns.}) 18. Bxe5 Bb5 19. Qb3 $14 {Black doesn't have proper compensation for his poor piece coordination.}) ({Worse is} 12... Nd5 13. Nc4 $1 Qa6 ({Equally bad is} 13... Qd8 14. Be5 Rc8 15. Nbd2 f6 16. Bd6 $16 {Vidit,S - Harikrishna,P Riadh 2017}) 14. Ne5 $1 Be8 15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 17. Qxd4 $16 {Black had no compensation for a pawn in Rogers,I - Toth,B Reggio Emilia 1984}) 13. b4 $1 {White bravely sacrifices a pawn to gain an important tempo for involving the rest of the pieces.} ({The timid} 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 g5 15. Bd2 Rb8 $1 {provides Black enough counterplay. Loginov,V - Yevseev,D St Petersburg 2004}) 13... Qxb4 14. a3 Qc5 15. Nd2 e5 {Black has to force the matters.} ({Something like} 15... Qh5 $2 16. N2c4 e5 17. Bd2 Rd8 18. Rb1 $16 {is very problematic as it will be no possibility to prevent the invasion of White's rook.}) ({The main point of 13.b3 can be seen in the following line:} 15... Bxd6 $2 16. Nb3 {Black loses his bishop} Qb6 17. Bxd6+ Kg8 18. Rb1 {Black is on the verge of collapse.}) 16. N2e4 (16. N6e4 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 {might lead to the same position.}) 16... Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Qb6 {The only adequate response, although the Qb6 might still be attacked.} 18. Rb1 Qc7 ({After} 18... Qa5 $2 19. Bd2 Qxa3 20. Qc2 {Black is nearly lost as 21.Ra1 or Rb7 is coming.}) 19. Bd2 f5 {This somewhat committing move should be played now.} ({There is no time for prophylactic move such as} 19... h6 $2 20. Qa4 f5 21. Rbc1 $1 fxe4 22. f4 $3 {White plays elegantly and joins all his pieces in the attack.} Bf6 23. fxe5 Qxe5 24. Rxc6 $18 {Black is nearly destroyed.}) 20. e3 $5 $146 {This aggressive move is a novelty. In all the preceding games, White played 20.g5.} ({For instance,} 20. Ng5 h6 21. Nf3 Kf7 22. e3 e4 23. Nxd4 Nxd4 24. exd4 Rab8 {Black gave his extra pawn, but managed to fully consolidate and solve all the issues in Gelfand,B - Adams,M Yerevan 2008}) 20... fxe4 {Accepting the challenge is the most natural reaction, although it isn't forced.} ({In the event of} 20... Rc8 $5 21. Qf3 Kg8 22. Nc5 {tthe Nc5 is untouchable in view of 23.Qd5+} e4 23. Nxe4 fxe4 24. Qxe4 $44 {White has a long-termed compensation for a piece as Black lacks connection between his rooks, and the pin on the c-file looks dangerous.}) ({Another interesting option is} 20... Rb8 $5 21. Rc1 Bxa3 (21... fxe4 22. Bxe4 Ke8 23. Qh5+ Kd8 24. exd4 {feels dangerous for a second player as the king is very unsafe. White will get few open files for his rooks.}) 22. Nc5 Bxc1 23. Qxc1 {Black has a big material advantage, but the poor piece coordination and pressure on the c-file make his practical task difficult.} Ke7 24. Nxd7 Kxd7 25. Qc4 $44 {White will soon involve his rook in the attack. Undoubtedly, White has full compensation.}) 21. Bxe4 {Black is at crossorads now. He has to choose between a few reasonable continuations. The most dangerous idea to deal with is 22.Qf3+, followed by Rfc1.} Bf6 $1 {The safeast response.} ({Dubious is} 21... Rd8 $6 22. Qf3+ Ke8 23. Rfc1 $40 {The Rd8 is useless.}) (21... Rc8 $5 {This is better than 21...Rd8, but the arising complications are dangerous for a second player} 22. Qf3+ Bf6 23. Rfc1 dxe3 ({After} 23... Qd6 24. Rb5 $1 dxe3 25. Rxc6 Qxd2 26. Rxf6+ Ke8 $8 {Black probably escapes, but it looks terrible for a human eye.}) 24. Bb4+ Kf7 (24... Ke8 $2 25. Qh5+ Kd8 26. fxe3 {is lost for Black because his pieces are paralyzed.}) 25. Bd5+ Ke8 $1 ({After} 25... Kg6 26. Qxe3 Qb6 27. Bc5 $36 {it is very hard for Black to secure his king.}) 26. Qh5+ g6 27. Qf3 exf2+ 28. Kg2 Bg5 {The engine claims equality, although this is hardly acceptable for a human player. The possible line is} 29. Rc4 $5 Qb6 30. Qf7+ Kd8 31. Be6 Rc7 32. Bd6 $1 Qxb1 {The only move!} 33. Bxc7+ Kxc7 34. Qxd7+ Kb8 35. Qd6+ Ka8 36. Qxc6+ Qb7 37. Kxf2 $11 {Black's extra pawn has no value.}) (21... Qd6 22. exd4 exd4 23. Rb7 {The active Rb7 increases White's attacking potential. In particular, 24.Rxd7, followed by 25.Qf3+ is a serious threat now.} Rd8 24. Re1 {It is very tough for Black to connect his rooks and secure the king. The play might continue:} h5 $5 {A sensible idea - Black is aiming to involve the rook along h-file.} 25. Bf4 Ne5 26. Rxd7 $1 Qxd7 (26... Rxd7 $2 27. Bf5 Bf6 28. Bxe5 Bxe5 29. Bxd7 {leads to fatal consequences for Black.}) 27. Bxe5 $44 {White has promising play for an exchange.}) 22. exd4 exd4 23. Rc1 ({The more forcing} 23. Bb4+ Nxb4 24. Bxa8 Nc6 25. Qc2 Qd6 {offers White no advantage.}) 23... Qb6 {The only move! Black has no other way of avoiding the pin because of Bd2-b4.} ({Bad is} 23... Rc8 $2 24. Bb4+ Ke8 25. Re1 Kd8 26. Bxc6 Bxc6 27. Re6 $18) 24. Re1 {The trickiest.} ({Another way of forcing a draw is} 24. Bxc6 Bxc6 25. Bb4+ Kf7 ({After} 25... Ke8 $2 26. Qb3 Kd8 27. Ba5 Qxa5 28. Rxc6 {White has a decisive attack.}) 26. Qb3+ Kg6 27. Qc2+ Kf7 $11) ({Or} 24. Rb1 Qc7 25. Rc1 Qb6 $11) 24... Re8 $1 {This cool-blooded move enables Black to maintain the balance.} 25. Bxc6 Bxc6 26. Bb4+ Kf7 27. Qb3+ Kg6 28. Qc2+ Kf7 $11 {It doesn't make sense to capture on c6 because the d4-passer will be very strong in this endgame.} *

