{[%evp 0,33,20,14,22,-14,-14,6,8,-1,31,27,25,12,8,-32,32,-7,5,28,23,-9,41,41,43,33,51,38,53,-12,-10,-14,53,16,18,-4]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. O-O e6 {A tricky setup. White is invited to show his cards. In the case of 5.d4 Black benefits from having the queen's knight on its initial spot, and after 5...cxd5 6.Nxd4 e5! the strong pawn center allows Black to easily solve the problems.} 5. c4 {I think this move is the most promising.} (5. d3 Nc6 6. Bf4 {can be well met by} Bd6 $1 {, and Black is doing well.} ({Instead,} 6... Be7 {takes us back to Chapter from Database 1.})) 5... d4 6. d3 Nc6 7. e3 Be7 {A solid choice. Black avoids the possible pin in advance. On the downside, it diminishes Black's control of e5, comparing to 7...Bd6.} 8. exd4 cxd4 9. Na3 {I like this active move: the Nc2 will attack d4 and also support the traditional b2-b4 advance.} O-O (9... Bxa3 $6 {is hardly a good idea:} 10. bxa3 O-O 11. Re1 Re8 12. Bf4 $1 {White prevents the freeing ...e6-e5.} Nd7 13. Bd6 Nf6 {This was Cheng,B - Ohanyan,E Kragero 2023 In my opinion, White has wrongly rejected the most natural} 14. c5 $146 Nd5 15. Ne5 $36 {The strong Bd6 makes Black's position very cramped.}) 10. Nc2 a5 ({Premature is} 10... e5 $6 11. Re1 Nd7 12. b4 $1 {White takes advantage of better development to force a favorable exchange.} Nxb4 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Rxe5 $16 {The vulnerability of Nd4 and poor Bc8 makes Black's position difficult. Matlakov,M - Rosen,E Chess.com INT 2022}) 11. Re1 Re8 {Black plans to move his Be7 to extend in the center.} ({Another common choice is} 11... Bd6 12. a3 e5 13. Rb1 a4 {Black managed to build a strong pawn center, but it cost him leaving the Bc8 on its initial spot.} 14. Nb4 $1 {The most energetic. Black has to take care of weak e5-pawn now.} Nd7 ({After} 14... Re8 15. c5 Bc7 16. Bg5 Nxb4 17. axb4 Bd7 18. Nd2 $14 {White has excellent prospects on the queenside due to his powerful Bg2. Moujan,P - Lund,S ICCF email 2020}) 15. Bd2 Re8 {This was Kazantsev,R - Shulman,B ICCF email 2012} (15... f6 {is very committing as it weakens the light squares around Kg8.} 16. Nh4 {White is ready to join his queen in the attack.} Ne7 17. Nd5 {White is aiming to exchange the main defender of d5.} Nc5 18. Nxe7+ Qxe7 19. Bb4 g5 {otherwise White could extend his initiative with ..f2-f4.} 20. Bd5+ Kh8 21. Nf3 Qd7 {Calio,M - Khokhlov,I ICCF email 2014} 22. Nd2 $146 Ne6 ({Of course,} 22... Nxd3 $2 {loses on a spot:} 23. Bxd6 Qxd6 24. Ne4 $18) 23. Rc1 Bxb4 24. axb4 Nc7 25. Be4 $14 {The q-side pawn majority and vulnerability of Kg8 offer White the better chances.}) {Here, I suggest the following new approach:} 16. Ng5 $146 {This move is especially effective when the f7 and h7-pawns are not fully covered.} h6 17. Ne4 Bf8 18. g4 $1 {Securing Ne4 and intending to open the files against Kg8 in the long run.} Nf6 19. Nxf6+ Qxf6 20. Nd5 Qg6 21. h3 $14 {I prefer White's chances due to strong Nd5 in this complex middlegame.}) (11... Ne8 {was played by many strong players, such are Korchnoi, Korobov and others. Still, the plan for connecting the pawns with ...f7-f6 and e6-e5 is rather slow.} 12. Bd2 f6 13. a3 a4 ({After} 13... e5 14. b4 Bg4 15. Qe2 $16 {White was much better as his extension on the queenside prevails. Forster,R - Kortschnoj,V Lenzerheide 2010}) 14. Nb4 $1 {White increases his pressure on the long diagonal. Also, in the case of ...e6-e5, White's knight will land on d5.} Nc7 15. b3 axb3 16. Qxb3 {White's pieces are coordinated much better now.} Kh8 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Qb6 $14 {Black has problems with covering his weak pawns. Odendahl,R - Lai,H Dieren 2019}) 12. b3 {The finachetto might put the d4-pawn in big danger. Also, a2-a3 becomes more attractive now when Black cannot fix the pawn structure with ...a5-a4.} Bf8 (12... Nd7 {was seen in Ionov,S - Vitiugov,N St Petersburg 2006 White should have ''fallen'' into the trap:} 13. Ncxd4 $1 $146 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bf6 15. Be3 Nc5 {The exchange is gone, but it's not a big deal:} 16. Nc6 $1 bxc6 17. Bxc5 Bxa1 18. Qxa1 $16 {The bishops dominate over the board. White has a huge positional advantage.}) 13. Bf4 $1 {This is the most effective way of development - it is vital to prevent ...e6-e5.} Ng4 {Insisting on the thematic advance.} ({After} 13... Nd7 $2 14. Nfxd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 e5 16. Nb5 exf4 17. Rxe8 Qxe8 18. Nc7 {Black's position was ruined in Baum,J - Seemann,J Sypniewo 2022}) 14. Bg5 $1 {An annoying provocative move.} f6 ({After} 14... Nf6 15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. Rxe5 $14 {the activity of White's pieces becomes threatening.}) 15. Bd2 {Now, the Ng4 is misplaced.} Qb6 16. Qe2 Bd7 17. Reb1 $14 {White has the more harmonious setup when b3-b4 is on the way. Paine,K - Landes,E ICCF email 2016} *

