{[%evp 0,45,20,14,26,-10,6,6,17,-1,3,5,12,2,3,-27,-25,-25,-24,-36,-29,-38,-35,-13,-30,-27,-21,-37,5,-11,-8,30,48,-22,-21,-36,-24,-76,-47,-72,-85,-74,-72,-90,-120,-102,-128,-85]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. O-O e6 5. c4 d4 6. d3 Nc6 7. e3 Bd6 {The most common way of development. Black takes more control of e5, so connecting the pawn with ...e6-e5 will be easier. The flip side is that d4 becomes temporarily vulnerable, and the Bd6 might be attacked by means of ..Na3-b5 or c4-c5.} ({Another possible setup starts with} 7... h6 {, when Black is aiming to place his bishop on d6 without allowing the nasty c1-g5.} 8. Na3 $1 {I find this most precise.} ({In the event of} 8. exd4 cxd4 9. Na3 {Black can obtain an excellent position by means of} Bxa3 $1 10. bxa3 O-O 11. Re1 Re8 12. Bf4 Ng4 $1 $132 {Now this active move is more effective as g5 isn't vacant for White's bishop.}) 8... e5 ({The rare} 8... Bd6 9. exd4 cxd4 10. Nc2 e5 {allows White to quickly extend with} 11. b4 O-O 12. c5 Bc7 13. b5 Ne7 14. Re1 Ng6 {This position was reached in Stremavicius,T - Kumsiashvili,N Al Ain 2013 Here I like the following way to regroup the forces:} 15. Nb4 $5 $146 Re8 16. Nd2 Bg4 17. Qa4 $14 {White has great piece coordination when the Bg2 plays a key role.}) 9. exd4 exd4 {This pawn structure is traditionally good for Black, but developed pieces are missing.} 10. Bf4 Bd6 {We have been following Warmerdam,M - Petkov,M Vrnjacka Banja 2023} ({I've examined also} 10... Be7 $146 11. Nb5 O-O 12. Bc7 Qd7 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 $14 {Black suffers from lack of harmony.}) 11. Bxd6 $146 Qxd6 12. Nb5 Qe7 (12... Qd8 13. Qe2+ Be6 14. Bh3 $14) 13. Qe1 $1 {A deep idea. White secures e5 for his knight in proper redaction.} ({The more natural} 13. Re1 Be6 14. Nh4 O-O {doesn't offer White anything special.}) 13... Be6 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Qxe5 O-O 16. Rae1 $36 {Black gets under strong pressure on the e-file and long diagonal.}) ({Another relatively rare move is} 7... e5 8. exd4 exd4 9. Bf4 Be7 10. Ne5 {As usual, White builds his pressure on the long diagonal.} Nxe5 11. Bxe5 O-O 12. Re1 Bd6 13. Bxf6 $1 {The knight is more effective in this position.} Qxf6 14. Nd2 Bf5 15. Be4 Bxe4 16. Nxe4 $14 {White has a clear advantage due to the superiority of Ne4 over the bishop. Meier,G - Cornejo,M Princeton 2012}) 8. exd4 cxd4 9. Na3 {I find this move most challenging for Black: it is easier to attack the d4-pawn like this.} O-O ({It hardly makes sense for Black to delay castle with} 9... e5 10. c5 $1 Bxc5 11. Nc4 Bg4 {The most natural way of covering the central pawn.} ({Dubious is} 11... Nd7 $6 12. Re1 O-O ({In case of} 12... f6 13. Nh4 $1 $36 {White has a powerful initiative as} O-O 14. Bd5+ Kh8 $2 {loses on the spot :} 15. Ng6+ hxg6 16. Qg4 $18) 13. Nfxe5 Ncxe5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Rxe5 $16 {The pressure on the long diagonal was very strong in Giri,A - So,W Wijk aan Zee 2015}) 12. Qb3 $1 {A double attack.} Bxf3 ({After} 12... Qe7 13. Re1 e4 14. dxe4 O-O 15. e5 Nd5 16. Bd2 $14 {White has the more active piece play.}) 13. Bxf3 Rb8 14. Re1 Nd7 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Godart,F - Villegas,P Brest 2019 My natural new idea is} 15. Bf4 $1 $146 O-O 16. Nxe5 Ndxe5 17. Bxe5 Nxe5 18. Rxe5 b6 19. Rae1 $14 {Although there are bishops of the opposite color, Black has to struggle for a draw as White's pieces are much more active.}) 10. Nc2 e5 11. b4 $1 {The best way to justify the previous Na3-c2 maneuver. From now the e5-pawn becomes more vulnerable.} Re8 (11... Nxb4 {The exchange isn't equal:} 12. Nxb4 Bxb4 13. Nxe5 Re8 14. Rb1 Bc5 15. Re1 $14 {White had a clear positional advantage due to strong Bg2. Matlakov,M - Koustav,C Chess.com INT 2021}) ({The prophylactic} 11... a6 {also was tested in many high-level games} 12. c5 Bc7 13. a4 {The threat of b4-b5 forces Black to switch to concrete play.} Nd5 ({In the event of} 13... Bg4 14. Re1 Qd7 15. b5 axb5 16. axb5 {White also manages to make lots of progress on the queenside.} Rxa1 17. Nxa1 Ne7 18. b6 Bb8 19. Bg5 $14 {The poor b8-bishop makes Black's position difficult. Laffranchise,L - Dunlop,G ICCF email 2017}) 14. Bd2 Bf5 {We have been following the game Oparin,G - Jumabayev,R Chess.com INT 2020 Among the interesting possibilities, I mostly like} 15. Re1 $5 $146 {Black is invited to enter tactical complications.} Bxd3 ({After} 15... Nc3 16. Bxc3 dxc3 17. b5 axb5 18. axb5 $36 {White's pieces are better mobilized, and the queenside passer is gonna be powerful in the long run.}) 16. Bg5 Bxc2 17. Qxc2 Ncxb4 ({After} 17... f6 18. Bd2 Kh8 19. b5 $14 {White's extension clearly overwhelms Black's extra pawn.}) 18. Qc4 Qd7 19. Nxe5 Qf5 20. Nf3 $36 {The powerful bishops and vulnerability of Nd5 provide White promising play for a pawn.}) 12. Re1 a6 {A vital prophylactic move. Black secures his Nc6 to keep e5-pawn covered.} ({Another natural way is} 12... Bg4 13. c5 Bc7 14. h3 Bh5 15. b5 Na5 16. Nb4 $36 {The Na5 is out of play, and c5-c6 becomes annoying. Bogdanovich,S - Kravtsiv,M Kyiv 2018}) 13. c5 Bf8 {The best retreat.} ({The natural} 13... Bc7 $6 {is clearly worse in view of} 14. Bg5 Bf5 ({After} 14... h6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Nfxd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 $16 {White is just a pawn up.}) 15. a4 h6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. b5 $16 {White's play on the queenside is lasting itself.}) 14. Bg5 {White doesn't mind exchanging the dark-squared bishop. It will potentially decrease the effect of ...e5-e4 advance.} Bf5 15. Nh4 {Unblocking the Bg2 and releasing the pressure on d3.} Bd7 16. a4 h6 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. a5 $1 {A vital move - White secures his pawn chain in view of possible ...a6-a5 break.} Rad8 {This was Vecek,M - Paleckis,E ICCF email 2018 Here I like the following new idea:} 19. Rb1 $5 $146 {Now the Nc2 isn't tied with defending the pawn. One of White's key ideas is transferring it on c4.} g5 ({An equal alternative is} 19... g6 $5 20. h3 Qg7 {Black moves his queen in order to start advancing the quuenside pawns.} ({Worse is} 20... Bg7 $6 21. Na3 $1 g5 22. Nf3 {Black hardly can allow the knight's invasion on d6.} Bf5 23. g4 Bg6 24. Nd2 $1 Bxd3 25. Ne4 Bxe4 26. Bxe4 $36 {White has an improved version, compared to text.}) 21. Na3 g5 ({After} 21... f5 $6 22. b5 axb5 23. Rxb5 {White's play on the q-side prevails.}) 22. Nf3 Bf5 {Black's pieces are well-coordinated now, so White has to seriously deal with ...e5-e4.} 23. g4 Bg6 24. Nd2 $1 {A well-timed sacrifice.} Bxd3 25. Rb3 Bg6 26. Ne4 $44 {White has an interesting play for a pawn. Both knights have potential outposts in Black's camp.}) 20. Nf3 Bf5 {Balck shows his intention to break through with e5-e4 or even capture on d3.} ({Equally possible is} 20... Bg4 21. h3 Bh5 22. g4 Bg6 23. Nd2 $1 {The same approach - White cannot let Black push ...e5-e4.} Bxd3 24. Ne4 Bxe4 25. Bxe4 $44) 21. Nd2 $1 Bxd3 22. Ne4 Bxe4 23. Bxe4 $44 {Full control over the light squares provides White sufficient compensation for a pawn.} *

