{[%evp 0,43,26,26,26,-10,40,25,67,46,59,53,47,47,47,51,55,42,40,26,26,48,44,27,46,55,55,44,37,44,38,0,44,44,56,41,60,58,51,50,45,42,47,47,52,52]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nd7 {This hardly can be called sideline nowadays - it is equally common as 2...Nc6, as was covered in 1st Database. Black's main idea is still ...e7-e5, while 3.d4 Nb6 or 3...b5 make it much more difficult for White to play c2-c4.} 3. d4 b5 4. Nc3 {I find this move well-timed as the double attack forces Black to waste a tempo for c7-c6.} c6 5. Bg2 {The most natural way of development. Of course, White plans to activate the light-squared bishop by pushing ..e2-e4.} (5. e4 b4 6. Ne2 dxe4 7. Nd2 {is worth attention, although after} e3 8. fxe3 Bb7 9. Bg2 e6 10. O-O Ngf6 {I am unsure if White can take advantage of his development advantage while the pawn structure isn't optimal.}) 5... Ngf6 (5... e6 6. O-O Ngf6 {is another posssible move order.}) (5... b4 {temporarily diminshes White's control of e4, but weakens c5.} 6. Na4 e6 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Re1 a5 9. Nd2 $14 {White's pieces are better mobilized, and e2-e4 is to follow soon. Shyam,S - Divya,D chess24.com INT 2022}) ({The attempt to build a Stonewall setup with} 5... f5 6. O-O Ngf6 {, as in Hillarp Persson,T - Lagunow,R Barcelona 2019} 7. Ng5 $1 $146 Nb6 {It is necessary to cover e6.} 8. a4 $1 {Interrupting opponent's natural development.} b4 9. a5 bxc3 ({After} 9... Nc4 10. b3 Nxa5 11. Na2 e6 12. Bd2 Qb6 13. Qe1 $16 {White regains the pawn and obtains a much better position because Black has many weak spots in his camp.}) 10. axb6 cxb2 11. Bxb2 Qxb6 12. Ba3 $36 {White's lead in development clearly overweights Black's extra pawn. Black struggles to the castle because the exchange on f8 will follow every time after...e7-e6.}) 6. O-O e6 7. a3 {The last preparations before pushing e2-e4 - White secures his Nc3.} Be7 ({Also after} 7... Bb7 8. e4 $1 dxe4 9. Ng5 {White seizes initiative as Black isn't in time to unblock the Bb7. For instance,} c5 10. Ngxe4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Bd5 12. Re1 $16 {Neef,M - Henriquez Villagra,C Barcelona 2019}) 8. e4 $1 {It turns out that White has no reason for delaying this move.} Nxe4 ({In case Black ignores the last move with} 8... O-O 9. e5 Ne8 10. h4 Nc7 11. Re1 a5 12. Bg5 $14 {he finds himself in a cramped position when White has excellent attacking prospects. Arsovic,Z - Dragnev,V Belgrade 2021}) ({After} 8... dxe4 9. Ne5 Bb7 10. Qe2 O-O 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. Rd1 Rfd8 13. Nxe4 $14 {Black is doomed to passive defense as the b7 remains passive.}) 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qc7 12. Bxe4 Bb7 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Meier,G - Schneider,I Playchess.com INT 2020 Here I suggest} 13. Qh5 $5 $146 {Proovking Black to weaken the dark squares.} g6 {Otherwise, Black cannot castle.} 14. Qf3 O-O 15. a4 {White is aiming to create new weaknesses on the other side, either.} b4 ({In the event of} 15... Rab8 16. Bh6 Rfd8 17. b3 {White is well-prepared for the freeing ...c6-c5. For instance,} c5 18. axb5 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 Rxb5 20. Rfd1 $14 {Black has no compensation for his weaknesses.}) 16. Rd1 Rfd8 ({Of course, not} 16... Qxe5 $2 17. Rd7 $18) 17. Bf4 Rab8 {Black's only adequate idea is unblocking the Bb7.} 18. h4 c5 19. Rxd8+ Bxd8 {The misplaced d8-bishop makes it possible for White to take control over the d-file.} 20. Bxb7 Qxb7 21. Qxb7 Rxb7 22. Rd1 $14 {Black suffers from lack of space.} *

