{[%evp 0,29,26,26,26,-10,25,25,49,43,45,21,33,25,25,25,34,35,54,46,31,26,36,39,37,33,42,38,52,55,46,43]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nd7 3. d4 Nb6 {This move is by far Black's top choice. Moving the knight twice at the beginning isn't recommended in most cases, but it is justified by preventing (or making much tougher) the key ..c2-c4 break.} 4. Nc3 $5 {I like this tricky move: White assumes that the opponent will place his bishop on f5. Therefore, taking control of e4 in advance makes sense, so Nf3-h4 will be more effective.} (4. Bg2 Bf5 5. O-O e6 {was tested many times on the high level, and it was proved to be very solid for the second player.}) 4... Bf5 ({Black can leave the c8-bishop for a while with} 4... Nf6 {, but after} 5. Bg2 {he has to show his cards.} Bf5 ({In case Black first secures h7 for his bishop with} 5... h6 {Van Foreest,J - Riazantsev,A Chess.com INT 2022 I suggest the energetic} 6. e4 $1 $146 dxe4 ({Equally possible is} 6... Nxe4 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. Ne5 Bf5 9. f3 $1 e3 ({After} 9... exf3 10. Qxf3 Be6 11. Qf2 $36 {White's initiative on the k-side is too strong.}) 10. f4 c6 11. Bxe3 $14 {White has much more space, and the e5 is very strong.}) 7. Ne5 Bf5 8. f3 $1 {The same idea as after 6...Nxe4 - it is very risky for Black to capture on f3 and open the f-file.} exf3 9. Qxf3 Bc8 10. d5 $1 {Now it is much tougher for Black to develop his minor pieces.} g6 11. Be3 Bg7 12. O-O-O O-O 13. Bd4 $44 {The extra pawn doesn't really tell for now, while White's pieces are much more active.}) ({Black may also deviate from placing his bishop on f5 with} 5... g6 6. a4 a5 7. O-O Bg7 {, but then} 8. Re1 $146 {allows White to take the upper hand in the center.} O-O ({After} 8... Ne4 9. Qd3 $1 Nxc3 (9... Bf5 10. Nh4 $14) 10. Qxc3 O-O 11. b3 Bf5 12. Ba3 Re8 13. Nh4 Be6 14. Rad1 $14 {White has th emore harmonious setup, and e2-e4 will secure some space advantage.}) 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Rxe4 Bf5 12. Re1 $14 {White has a superior pawn structure. Black struggles to challenge the center either with c7-c5 or e7-e5.}) 6. Nh4 {of course, this is White's key idea.} e6 {Black accepts the doubled pawns to maintain control of e4} ({After} 6... Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 {White should act aggressively:} 8. g4 Bg6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. g5 Nh5 {Not a great move to make, but what else to do? Statically, Black's position is acceptable, but there is a deal breaker:} 11. Nxd5 $3 Nxd5 12. c4 {Now the Bg2 is a real monster!} Nb6 ({After} 12... Nhf4 13. Bf3 $16 {White regains the piece and obtains a much better position.}) 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. Bc6+ Nd7 15. c5 $16 {White has 2 pawns for a piece, while the Nh5 will be out of play, and the pin causes serious Black problems.}) (6... Bg6 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. e4 e6 {was seen in Firouzja,A - Fedoseev,V Chess.com INT 2020 Here I like the simple} 9. e5 $146 Nfd7 10. Ne2 c5 11. c3 Rc8 12. O-O $14 {White is better due to space advantage and bishop pair.}) 7. Nxf5 exf5 8. O-O c6 9. Qd3 Qd7 (9... g6 10. f3 Bg7 11. e4 $14 {also gives White the upper hand in the center.}) 10. f3 $1 {The traditional e2-e4 will allow White to activate the bishops.} Rd8 11. Bh3 g6 12. e4 $16 {Black found himself in a difficult position in Nenezic,M - Prohaszka,P Hungary 2022}) 5. Nh4 Bg4 {Black doesn't confess his bishop so early.} ({The alternative is} 5... e6 6. Nxf5 exf5 7. Qd3 {White gains a tempo by attacking the f5-pawn. The Qd3 might be involved in various ways.} g6 8. Bg2 c6 ({The other natural continuations are:} 8... Bg7 9. a4 a5 10. b3 {Obviously, a3-f8 is a very attractive diagonal for the c1-bishop,} Ne7 ({After} 10... Nf6 11. Bg5 c6 12. e3 O-O 13. Ne2 Nbd7 14. c4 $14 {Black has no compensation for his structural drawbacks and weak d5-pawn.}) 11. Ba3 O-O 12. e3 c6 13. Ne2 Re8 14. c4 $14 {Black was doomed to passive defense in Sedlak,N - Lu,M Arandjelovac 2021}) (8... Nf6 9. O-O Bg7 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. e3 $14 {It is only a matter of time before White will play ..c2-c4 and put strong pressure on the long diagonal. Bernadskiy,V - Willow,J Cattolica 2022}) 9. a4 a5 10. O-O Bg7 {We have been following the game Gaal,Z - Esipenko,A chess24.com INT 2022} (10... Nf6 {took place in 3 games. Here I mostly like the following ambitious idea:} 11. f3 $1 $146 Bg7 12. e4 fxe4 13. fxe4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 $36 {White managed to activate both bishops, so Black is in trouble.}) {At this point, I suggest the restricting strategy that starts with} 11. b3 $146 Nf6 12. Bg5 {Getting rid of a bishop before playing the consolidating e2-e3.} Nbd7 13. e3 h6 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Ne2 $14 {Black lacks constructive ideas, when c2-c4 will put pressure on the d5.}) 6. Qd3 {A usual spot for White's queen in this line. This time it makes it possible to play e2-e4.} Nf6 ({Another considerable option is} 6... e6 7. e4 c6 ({I examined also} 7... Nf6 $146 8. e5 Nfd7 {We have an original version of French Defence.} 9. h3 Bh5 10. Be2 Bxe2 11. Nxe2 {Moving the c3-knigh is an achievement for White, who can strengthen his central pawn chain.} c5 12. c3 Be7 13. Nf3 Rc8 14. O-O $14 {White's attacking prospects overwhelm Black's play on the queenside.}) 8. h3 Bh5 {This was Svane,R - Kovalenko,I Chess.com INT 2023 Here I like the following new approach:} 9. exd5 $1 $146 exd5 (9... cxd5 {is met by} 10. Qb5+ $1 Qd7 11. a4 $14 {Black find hard times with covering the diagonal a4-e8.}) ({In case of} 9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Bg2 $14 {the symmetrical pawn structure doesn't offer Black an easy play: any developing move with Bf8 will be met with Nh4-f5.}) 10. Qe3+ {A deep idea. Black's natural development is interrupted.} Qe7 (10... Be7 11. Bd2 $1 Qd7 12. g4 $14) 11. Bd3 Qxe3+ ({The careless} 11... Nf6 $6 12. f4 $1 $16 {leaves Black with an awkward Bh5 that might be trapped. Therefore, Black loses material.}) 12. Bxe3 Bb4 13. Nf5 $14 {White has the better piece coordination.}) 7. Bg2 e6 8. O-O Be7 {This was Rechlis,G - Postny,E Israel 2021} ({I also examined} 8... c6 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 Be7 11. Re1 O-O ({After} 11... Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Bh5 13. Qe5 $1 $14 {White's positional advantage is undeniable.}) 12. h3 Bh5 13. Ng5 $1 {It makes sense to deviate from exchanging knights. White invites the move ...h7-h6, after which Black's k-side is somewhat exposed.} h6 14. Ngf3 Nfd7 15. c4 $14 {White has more space, and the Nb6 is awkward.}) {My natural improvement over White's play is} 9. h3 $146 Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 (10... Nfd7 {might invite dangerous tactical complications:} 11. Nf5 $1 Bg6 12. Nxg7+ Kf8 13. Bh6 $1 Bxd3 14. Nxe6+ Ke8 15. Nxd8 Ba6 {The Nd8 is trapped now, but White grabs lots of pawns.} 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 18. Bxd5+ Kg6 19. Bf4 $14 {four pawns overwhelm the piece in this unbalanced endgame.}) 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. e4 {A well-timed advance. White takes advantage of his unopposite Bg2.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 c6 15. b3 $14 {After c2-c4, White will find a way to break through with ..d4-d5. Black is doomed to passive defense.} *

