{[%evp 0,23,26,26,19,-10,44,22,35,3,37,47,25,27,25,-3,35,19,24,22,26,13,30,2,35,34]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 {This original idea has gained popularity in the last two years. Among the top players on Black's side there Magnus Carlsen, Vladimir Fedoseev, Pavel Eljanov and others. Black opts for an early fianchetto to properly meet both c2-c4 and e2-e4.} 3. c4 {I find this move well-timed: the long diagonal is somewhat exposed now, so it yields White definite tactical resources.} dxc4 ({In case of} 3... e6 {it makes sense for White to eliminate ...dxc4 option by means of} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg2 Nf6 6. O-O Bb7 7. d3 {This move mostly suits Reti players. White is aiming to take advantage of his pawn majority on the kingside.} (7. d4 $5 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bf4 {is another promising option. This position mostly arises from Queen's Indian Defence, when the early ...d7-d5 allows White to fix a favorable pawn structure.}) 7... Be7 8. Nd4 $1 {White unblocks his bishop while the knight is heading on f5.} Qd7 ({Worse is} 8... g6 $6 9. e4 dxe4 10. dxe4 O-O 11. Nc3 $16 {The threat of e4-e5 is especially dangerous now when the dark squares around Black's king are so weak. Shevchenko,K - Ovsejevitsch,S Polanica Zdroj 2021}) 9. e4 $1 {White secures f5 for his knight.} dxe4 10. dxe4 Bxe4 {The most challenging move - Black grabs the central pawn.} ({After} 10... Nc6 11. Nf5 O-O-O 12. Qxd7+ Rxd7 13. Nxe7+ Rxe7 14. Nc3 $14 {White has the better endgame due to powerful bishops.}) 11. Bxe4 Nxe4 12. Re1 {White's development advantage starts to tell now.} c5 $1 $146 {This is definitely the best.} ({After} 12... f5 13. Nc3 O-O 14. Nxe4 fxe4 15. Rxe4 Rf7 16. Bf4 $36 {White had a free initiative due to more active pieces in Czebe,A - Tran,T Chennai 2019}) 13. Rxe4 Nc6 ({After} 13... cxd4 14. Rxd4 Qb7 15. Nc3 Nc6 16. Qf3 $14 {White's pieces are much more active.}) 14. Rxe7+ $1 {White manages to avoid the nasty pin by giving up the exchange.} Nxe7 15. Qf3 Rd8 16. Ne2 O-O 17. Nbc3 $14 {The minor pieces overwhel}) 4. Na3 ({The other way of regaining the pawn is} 4. Qa4+ Nd7 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O e6 7. Qxc4 Ngf6 {, but the vulnerability of c4 often helps Black to solve his issues.}) 4... Bb7 ({The ambitious} 4... e5 {was seen in Svane,R - Urazayev,A Chess.com INT 2023 In my opinion, it can be well met by} 5. Qa4+ $1 $146 c6 6. Qxc4 Be6 7. Qc2 f6 8. Bg2 $14 {Black struggles to complete his development. White aims to open the position with ..d2-d4 in the long run.}) 5. Nxc4 e6 ({Black can damage White's pawn chain, but it costs him a valuable bishop:} 5... Bxf3 6. exf3 e6 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. f4 $36 {The powerful g2-bishop prevails.}) (5... Nf6 6. Bg2 e6 {is another possible moves order.}) 6. Bg2 Nf6 ({It makes a little sense to keep the knight on its initial spot:} 6... Be7 {, as in Svane,R - Vogel,R Katowice 2022 runs into} 7. Nce5 $1 $146 {The threat of 8.Nxf7 is annoying.} Nd7 8. Nxd7 Qxd7 9. Ne5 {White still benefits from opposition along the diagonal!} Qc8 10. Qa4+ $16) (6... Nd7 7. O-O Be7 $5 {is very rare, although it is probably the safest option.} ({After} 7... Ngf6 {Amin,B - Fedoseev,V Abu Dhabi 2021} 8. Nce5 $1 $146 {Black faces problems similar to the mainline.} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Bxg2 10. Qa4+ $1 {An important intermediate move.} c6 11. Kxg2 Qd5+ 12. f3 $1 {This is the point! White isn't obliged to retreat the knight.} Rc8 13. d4 $14 {Superiority in the center offers White the better play.}) 8. Rb1 {I like this approach: White grabs space and prevents ...c7-c5.} Ngf6 ({After} 8... c5 9. Nce5 $1 Bf6 10. Qa4 Bxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 $14 {The pin still causes definite Black problems.}) 9. b4 O-O 10. d3 Rc8 11. Bd2 $14 {White had the more pleasant play in Vejmelek,M - Soukup,J Karlovy Vary 1998 The only attempt to develop any counterplay is} c5 {, but after} 12. b5 $1 a6 13. a4 Nd5 14. e4 Nb4 15. Qb3 {Black's pieces are passive, and the b6 is weak.}) 7. Nce5 $1 {It turns out that White can pose Black concrete problems because of unprotected Bb7. In particular, there is a threat of 8.Nxf7, followed by Ne5/g5+.} Qc8 {A sad necessity. Of course, the Qc8 is placed awkwardly now.} ({The careless} 7... Be7 $4 {loses on a spot:} 8. Nxf7 Kxf7 9. Ne5+ $18) 8. O-O Bd6 9. d4 O-O {We have been following the game Rechlis,G - Nabaty,T Jerusalem 2019 White could have extended his initiative with} 10. Bg5 $1 $146 Ne4 ({After} 10... Nbd7 11. Rc1 h6 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Nc6 {Black's setup is very crumped because of dominating Nc6.}) 11. Rc1 Nxg5 12. Nxg5 $36 {The lack of development feels significant now when White's pieces are so active.} *

