1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 Bf5 {This developing move has a serious drawback: The b7-pawn is vulnerable and the placement of the Bf5 is unstable, as it can be attacked by the Nf3.} ({The other possibilities are:} 7... Ne4 {This pseudo-active move is dubious, as it weakens d5 and delays the development of the queenside pieces.} 8. Nc3 Bf5 ({The position that arises after} 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 dxc4 10. a5 {is covered in Chapter 7.}) 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Qa3 $14 {White's position is much more harmonious.}) (7... Na6 {is a serious concession, too, since the Na6 is misplaced. Therefore, the exchange on d5 is well-timed now.} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 ({The solid} 8... cxd5 {Bulatova,K - Tokarev,I Kazan 2017 traditionally runs into} 9. Qb3 $1 $146 Qb6 10. Qxb6 axb6 11. Nc3 Nb4 12. Ra3 $14 {, and the vulnerability of the doubled b-pawns starts to tell.}) 9. Nc3 Bf5 10. Ng5 $1 {A decent way of taking control of e4.} Ndb4 11. e4 Bc8 12. Be3 e5 13. d5 h6 14. Nf3 $14 {The strong d5-pawn makes Black's position somewhat cramped.}) ({The second fianchetto} 7... b6 {makes little sense and leads to a passive position:} 8. Nc3 Bb7 {Nyvlt,O - Tichy,M Czech Republic 2013} 9. a5 $146 e6 ({After} 9... dxc4 10. Ne5 Qc8 11. Nxc4 b5 12. a6 $1 {, interrupting the coordination between opponent's pieces,} Bxa6 13. Na5 $36 {, White has a free initiative.}) 10. axb6 axb6 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. Qa4 Nbd7 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Bf4 {Despite the symmetrical pawn structure, Black is under strong positional pressure - almost all White's pieces are more active and the a-file is open at White's disposal.}) (7... Bg4 {was never seen in tournament practice. Indeed, Black doesn't achieve much by giving up the bishop pair:} 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 e6 10. b3 Nbd7 11. Nc3 $14) 8. Nc3 dxc4 {This is the most challenging move for White.} ({In case of} 8... Na6 9. cxd5 cxd5 (9... Nxd5 {transposes.}) 10. Qb3 Qb6 11. Ra3 $14 {, the poor placement of the Na6 is obvious.}) 9. a5 {A multi-purpose move: It prevents Black from connecting his pawns with ..b7-b5 and vacates a4 for the queen.} ({Instead,} 9. Ne5 {, as was played in most games, is met with} Ng4 $1 {and Black is fine.}) 9... Nbd7 ({After} 9... Ne4 10. Nh4 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Be6 {Maltsevskaya,A - Eriksson,C Pardubice 2018 , White could have occupied the centre:} 12. e4 $146 Na6 13. f4 {, and then Black is more or less forced to weaken his king:} f5 14. exf5 gxf5 15. Rb1 Rb8 16. Re1 Nc7 17. Ba3 $36 {The weaknesses in Black's camp more than outweigh his extra pawn.}) 10. Nh4 $1 $146 {As was mentioned before, the Bf5 is unsecured. This factor makes it possible for White to expand in the centre.} ({Much weaker is} 10. Qa4 $6 b5 11. axb6 axb6 12. Qxa8 Qxa8 13. Rxa8 Rxa8 $11 {Keymer,V (2664) -Abdusattorov,N (2651) chess24.com INT 2022}) 10... Be6 11. e4 b5 12. f4 $1 {White isn't afraid of ghosts! The c4-pawn is strong now, but practically all of Black's pieces are passive. Now the threat of f4-f5 is very annoying.} ({Somewhat less convincing is} 12. axb6 axb6 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 14. f4 Rd8 {, and Black has a definite counterplay.}) 12... Bg4 13. Qc2 {The Bg4 is still in big danger!} c5 14. d5 b4 15. Nd1 $36 {White's central pawns are very strong and they are supported by the activity of his pieces, while the c4-pawn might fall soon.} *

