{[%evp 0,29,19,24,24,4,34,24,24,6,11,3,3,6,3,-3,7,8,17,17,19,19,25,19,19,7,24,24,24,23,39,44]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 a5 {This is Black's top choice if he avoids 7...dxc4, which is covered in chapters 5 and 6. It prevents White from expanding further on the queenside and secures the b4-square for a knight.} (7... Be6 {will be analysed in Chapter 4.}) 8. cxd5 {It turns out that Black's last move also weakens b5, so White reasonably decides to release the pressure in the centre.} ({The attempt to maintain the tension with} 8. Na3 {is somewhat artificial, as the Na3 is misplaced. Therefore, after} Be6 $1 9. Qb3 Na6 10. Ng5 {, as in Adly,A - Antipov,M Moscow 2019 , Black could have obtained an excellent position, had he continued} Bg4 $1 11. Re1 h6 12. Nf3 Be6 $11) 8... cxd5 (8... Nxd5 9. Nc3 Nb4 {was seen in Tukhaev,A - Laxman,R Hyderabad 2019. Here White had no reason to deviate from the most ambitious} 10. e4 $146 Bg4 11. Be3 e5 {Black has to play actively.} 12. d5 cxd5 13. exd5 N8a6 14. d6 $14 {In this complex position, White's strong d6-passer puts Black under some pressure.}) 9. Nc3 (9. Qb3 Nc6 10. Nc3 {is another way to reach the same position.}) 9... Nc6 10. Qb3 Nb4 ({A solid but rather passive alternative is} 10... e6 11. Bf4 h6 ({I've also examined:} 11... Nh5 $146 12. Be3 Nf6 13. Nb5 Bd7 14. Ne5 {The activity of his knights puts Black under definite pressure. For instance} Nxe5 15. dxe5 Ng4 16. Bc5 Re8 17. f4 $14 {Black's position is cramped and the Ng4 is misplaced.}) 12. Nb5 Ne8 ({Worse is} 12... Ne4 $6 13. Qe3 g5 14. Bc7 Qe7 15. Ne5 $16) 13. h4 f6 14. Rfd1 g5 15. Bd2 $1 $146 {This retreat leaves White the possibility to push ..e2-e4.} ({Less precise is} 15. Be3 Rf7 16. Bh3 Bf8 $11 {Levin,G - Kozul,Z Terme Catez 2022}) 15... Nd6 ({The following way to regroup the pieces,} 15... Rf7 16. Rac1 Bf8 {, runs into} 17. Qd3 $1 {, and after e2-e4 White will increase his initiative in the centre.}) 16. hxg5 hxg5 17. Ne1 Rf7 18. Nc2 $14) ({Another logical continuation might be} 10... b6 $146 11. Rd1 Bf5 ({Worse is} 11... Ba6 $6 12. Ne5 Nb4 13. Bd2 $16 {, and 14.Nb5 will follow. The Ba6 isn't doing much.}) 12. Bf4 Nb4 13. Rac1 {Putting the rook on the open file and covering c2.} Rc8 14. h3 $1 {A decent move. White is intending to play g3-g4 and deprive the Bf5 of the h7-b1 diagonal.} h5 15. Ne5 Ne4 16. g4 hxg4 17. hxg4 {White achieved the goal.} Be6 18. Nb5 $14 {Black is doomed to passive defence.}) 11. Nb5 $1 $146 {In this symmetrical position, White's extra tempo is important. In particular, White is first to attack the Nb4.} ({Harmless is} 11. Na2 Nxa2 12. Qxa2 Qb6 $11 {Giri,A - Duda,J Chess.com INT 2021}) 11... Bf5 12. Bd2 Bc2 13. Qa3 Nc6 {A sad necessity.} 14. Rfc1 Be4 15. Bf4 $14 {White has long-lasting positional pressure.} *

