{[%evp 0,43,27,25,28,6,43,25,36,-7,-7,-7,2,1,9,-30,-1,-1,-3,-6,-18,-10,-1,-78,-39,-29,-9,15,12,-1,10,20,48,41,46,38,70,58,50,65,64,70,70,69,63,63]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 g6 6. O-O Nbd7 {In similar to the main line 6...Bg7 and 7...Ne4, this move is mainly aimed for defending the Pc4. However, it takes few tempi and allows White to quickly take the upper hand in the centre.} 7. Qc2 Nb6 ({After} 7... b5 $6 8. Ne5 Bb7 9. b3 $16 {White will get the pawn back, while ...b7-b5 made Black's position very dicey.}) 8. e4 Bg7 ({After} 8... Bg4 $6 9. Be3 Bg7 {Adibekian,R - Jentsch,D Wesel Undeloh 2015 The simplest is} 10. Nbd2 $146 O-O 11. h3 Be6 12. Ng5 $16) 9. a4 a5 {This move is practically forced.} ({Pointless is} 9... O-O $6 10. a5 Nbd7 11. Rd1 $16 {The Pc4 will fall soon, and Nd7-b6 turns a loss of time.}) 10. Rd1 O-O 11. Na3 {There are few good-looking alternatives at White's disposal, but I like this move: if the Pc4 falls, the Nd7-b6 manoevre will be pointless.} Be6 ({The exchange of Bc8 is another concession:} 11... Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 $16 {Nikologorskiy,K - Grachev,B St Petersburg 2012}) ({The prophylactic} 11... h6 {vacates e6 for the bishop, but weakens the k-side, and after} 12. h3 Be6 13. Ne5 Ne8 14. f4 $36 {White can start advancing his k-side pawns, and the Ne5 is stable. Cori,J - Rambaldi,F New York 2018}) 12. h3 Ne8 ({It makes a little sense to attack the Ph3:} 12... Qc8 13. Kh2 Rd8 14. Be3 $16 {Black's pieces were misplaced, and the Pc4 seems to fall anyways. Eljanov,P - Ramirez Alvarez, A Chess.com INT 2019}) 13. Ng5 Bc8 ({After} 13... Bxd4 14. Be3 c5 15. Nb5 $16 {Black's will be left without his main defender.}) 14. Nxc4 {Eventually White took the pawn in favorable situation.} Nxc4 15. Qxc4 e5 {Only this break might offer Black some counter-play.} 16. Nf3 {The knight did its job, and now it is coming back to make g5 vacant for the bishop.} exd4 {This was Ding,L - Giri,A Shenzhen 2017 I can present the following valuable novelty:} 17. Bg5 $1 $146 ({Instead,} 17. Nxd4 $6 Be6 18. Qd3 Nc7 {allows Black to mibilize his forces and equalize.}) 17... Qd6 ({After} 17... Be6 18. Bxd8 Bxc4 19. Be7 Be2 20. Rd2 Bxf3 21. Bxf3 $16 {there is no real compensation for an exchange.}) 18. Nxd4 Nc7 19. Nf5 $1 {This is the best way to make use of promising opposition along the d-file.} Qe6 20. Nh6+ Bxh6 21. Qxe6 Bxe6 22. Bxh6 $16 {The strong unopposite Bh6 makes Black's position hughly unpleasant.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bonus Chapter 5"]
[Black "4...dxc4 5.Bg2 g6 - no 6...Ne"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D73"]
[Annotator "GM Michael Roiz"]
[PlyCount "55"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. a4 O-O {This natural move was made by many strong players, such as Anand, Nepomniatchi, Malakhov and others. However, I find it less challenging than 7...Ne4: it allows White to immediately regain the pawn in a favourable situation.} ({Worth attention is} 7... Be6 8. Ng5 Bd5 $146 {Curiously, this natural move has never been tried yet.} ({Less consistent is} 8... Bd7 9. Na3 h6 10. Nf3 Be6 11. Ne5 {Eventually the c4-pawn will fall.} Bd5 {This was Vignesh,N - Paravyan,D Moscow 2014. There was nothing wrong with} 12. Naxc4 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 O-O 14. f3 Nbd7 15. e4 $14 {White has a clear positional edge due to his strong centre.}) ({Black can hardly fight for equality with} 8... Qd7 9. Nxe6 Qxe6 10. Na3 {The Qe6 is awkwardly placed and the c4-pawn should fall sooner or later anyway.} O-O 11. Qc2 Na6 12. e3 $14 {Rawlings,A - Kazoks,A ICCF email 2012}) 9. f3 $1 {This quiet move secures White a strong pawn centre.} ({Instead, after} 9. e4 h6 10. exd5 hxg5 11. dxc6 Nxc6 {the open h-file offers Black definite counterplay.}) 9... h6 10. Nh3 {The Ng5 has done its job.} O-O 11. e4 Be6 12. Be3 a5 {Fixing the b4-spot is a slight achievement here.} 13. Nf4 Bc8 14. Na3 $14) ({Another somewhat artificial continuation,} 7... Na6 {, was tried twice by opening expert GM Volokitin.} 8. Na3 Be6 9. Ng5 Qd7 10. Nxe6 Qxe6 11. e3 $1 {A solid choice. The d4-pawn is secured and White can attack the c4-pawn soon.} Ne4 {Dubov,D - Volokitin,A Batumi 2018} 12. Nxc4 $146 Qxc4 13. Bxe4 O-O 14. b3 Qe6 15. Bg2 Rfd8 16. Ba3 $14) (7... Nd5 {also was employed in high-level games.} 8. e4 Nc7 {Giesemann,S - Even,R GER email 2014 Here I strongly recommend:} ({After} 8... Nb4 9. Na3 Bg4 10. Nxc4 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Bxd4 (11... Qxd4 12. Qb3 a5 13. Be3 Qf6 14. Bg4 $16) 12. Bh6 {The Ke8 is stuck in the centre, so White's initiative overwhelms the pawn.}) 9. Be3 $146 O-O 10. Qe2 b5 {Otherwise the Nd5-c7 manoeuvre has no point.} 11. Rd1 a6 12. Nc3 Bb7 {Black managed to keep his extra pawn, but his king feels unsafe, as almost all the pieces are on the opposite side.} 13. h4 Nd7 (13... h6 14. d5 $36) 14. h5 {The advance of the h-pawn is a standard attacking measure in such cases.} Qe8 15. h6 Bh8 16. Ng5 f6 17. Nh3 $36 {Black's setup with Bh8 is cramped and f2-f4 will follow soon.}) 8. Na3 Be6 ({In case of} 8... Na6 9. Nxc4 Be6 10. b3 {White manages to harmoniously develop his pieces and maintain his space superiority} Bd5 (10... Ne4 {, as in Matlakov,M - Bluebaum,M Lichess. org INT 2021, also can be well met by} 11. Ba3 $146 c5 12. e3 Nb4 13. Nfe5 $36 {The pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal is very annoying.}) 11. Ba3 {Making it tougher for Black to play ... c6-c5.} Rc8 12. Rc1 Re8 {We have been following the game Mamedyarov,S - Nepomniachtchi,I Paris 2019. Now what I like most is the following positional idea:} ({Premature is} 12... c5 $6 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Ne3 $16) 13. Qd3 $5 $146 c5 (13... Be4 14. Qe3 $14) 14. Rfd1 Nb4 15. Qb1 $36 {The opposition on the d-file looks very dangerous for Black.}) ({Too passive is} 8... Nbd7 9. Nxc4 Nb6 10. Nce5 {Following the classical rule: the side with a space advantage should deviate from exchanging too many pieces.} a5 11. b3 Bf5 12. Ba3 Nfd7 {This was Shimanov,A - Malakhov,V St Petersburg 2015. Here what I like most is the flexible} 13. Nd3 Be4 14. e3 Re8 15. Qe2 $14 {Black suffers due to lack of space and his poor b6-knight.}) ({After} 8... a5 9. Nxc4 Be6 10. Qc2 Na6 {Black acquires the b4-square for his knight, but} 11. Bd2 Nb4 12. Bxb4 axb4 13. Rfc1 Bd5 14. e3 $14 {made the b4-pawn vulnerable in Wallner,J - Koop, T Austria 2015}) ({The more active} 8... Ne4 9. Nxc4 Be6 10. Qc2 {also makes little sense as the Ne4 is unstable. For instance} Nd6 11. Nxd6 exd6 12. e4 Re8 13. Bg5 $14 {White was better due to his strong pawn centre. Ortiz,C - Permykov,A FICGS email 2017}) 9. Ng5 Bd5 10. e4 h6 11. exd5 hxg5 12. dxc6 Nxc6 13. d5 $1 {The strong Nd5 secures White some space advantage. From now on the e7-pawn is a target for White's rooks.} ({Weaker is} 13. Bxg5 Nxd4 14. Nxc4 Rc8 15. b3 Nd7 {Black had sufficient counterplay due to his strong Nd4 in Avrukh,B - Nabaty,T Beersheba 2013}) 13... Na5 ({After} 13... Nb4 14. Nxc4 Nfxd5 15. Bxg5 $36 {White's bishops were very strong and there was the possibility of increasing his initiative on the kingside with h4-h5. Jumabayev,R - Kobalia,M Moscow 2015}) 14. Bxg5 Qd7 ({Inferior is} 14... Qb6 15. Qe2 Rac8 16. Nb5 a6 17. Nc3 $16 {White was much better due to his space advantage and bishop pair in Jumabayev, R - Timofeev,A St Petersburg 2018}) 15. h4 Nb3 ({I've also examined} 15... Rad8 16. Qe1 $1 Nb3 17. Rd1 Qxa4 18. Qxe7 $36 {The strong d5-pawn is supported by powerful bishops, so Black's position seems dangerous.}) 16. Rb1 Qxa4 17. h5 gxh5 18. Bxf6 exf6 19. d6 Rad8 {Pascual Perez,N - Kahl,F LSS email 2018 Here I strongly recommend the following fresh idea:} 20. Bd5 $1 $146 {White's bishop joins the attack. The following line illustrates White's attacking potential:} Qb4 {Black not only attacks the d6-pawn but also threatens ...Nd2.} (20... f5 21. Nxc4 $36) 21. Qxh5 $1 Nd2 22. Rfd1 Nxb1 23. Kg2 $1 {A powerful quiet move: White threatens 24.Rh1.} ({Less effective is} 23. Nxc4 Rd7 24. Rxb1 Re8 $13) 23... Rd7 {The only move. Black needs to cover the f7-pawn} 24. Nc2 $1 {Another piece is joining the attack!} Qxb2 25. Nd4 f5 {Black cannot let White's knight reach f5} 26. Rh1 Re8 27. Ne6 $1 {A powerful tactical resource.} Rxe6 28. Bxe6 $36 {The bishop is untouchable in view of Qe8+. Black is under strong pressure.} *

