{[%evp 0,35,25,24,24,4,34,24,29,3,3,15,26,-8,5,2,12,17,7,-4,5,15,29,2,51,-2,17,-33,-3,32,47,52,86,72,63,69,69,83]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. a4 Ne4 8. Nc3 {White offers the knight's trade under favourable circumstances.} (8. Qc2 Nd6 9. e4 {is the most common alternative, but after} Na6 {Black often achieves sufficient counterplay because of Nb4-d3 ideas.}) 8... Nd6 ({Insufficient is} 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 O-O 10. a5 $1 {White grabs space and vacates a4 for his queen.} c5 ({After} 10... Be6 11. Qa4 Bd5 12. Re1 $14 {Black fails to set-up a blockade.}) 11. Qa4 Nc6 {This was Aditya, M - Ohanyan,E Paracin 2021} ({After} 11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 e5 13. Nc2 {the strong Bg2 offers White a powerful initiative.}) 12. Rd1 $1 $146 {Now White should have continued} cxd4 13. Nxd4 {The opposition on the d-file helps White to retain the pressure.} Nxd4 14. cxd4 Qc7 {Black is still up a pawn but won't be able to keep it much longer.} (14... Bg4 15. Qxc4 Rc8 16. Qd3 $14) 15. Be3 $1 {A decent consolidating move.} Bd7 (15... Rb8 16. Rdc1 b5 17. axb6 axb6 18. Rxc4 $14) 16. Qb4 {Now White regains the pawn.} Rab8 17. Rdc1 Rfc8 18. Qxe7 $14) 9. e4 Bg4 ({Another natural continuation is} 9... O-O {, but it only occurred in a couple of games so far.} 10. Qe2 Na6 ({I've also examined} 10... Bg4 $146 11. Rd1 Na6 12. e5 $1 {This is a good moment to lock in the Bg7.} ({Weaker is} 12. h3 $6 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 e5 $1 $132 {, and Black's knight is heading for d3.}) 12... Nf5 13. Qe4 $1 {A decent move. The queen's centralisation makes it possible to cover d4 and attack the bishop.} Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nb4 15. Be2 $14 {White manages to regain the pawn and maintain his space advantage.}) 11. Rd1 Nc7 {This position was seen in Wang,H - Rodshtein,M Khanty-Mansiysk 2019 In my opinion, White could have claimed superiority after} 12. e5 $146 Nf5 13. g4 Nh6 14. h3 $14 {The h6-knight is misplaced, and it is only a matter of time before White will take the pawn back.}) 10. Be3 Qc8 {The most common continuation. Black is aiming to prevent h2-h3 to keep the Nf3 pinned.} ({The alternatives are:} 10... O-O 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Na6 ({The attempt to meet White's expansion with} 12... e5 $146 {runs into} 13. dxe5 Bxe5 14. Qe2 Qe7 15. Rae1 Nd7 16. f4 $36 {, with a powerful initiative.}) 13. Qe2 {White keeps an eye on the c4-pawn and prepares the standard f2-f4.} Nb4 14. g4 $1 {A decent move. Now f5 isn't vacant for the Nd6, so e4-e5 is more effective.} a5 15. Rad1 Kh8 16. f4 $36 {White had a huge positional advantage in Sadhwani,R - Smirnov,A Chess.com INT 2020.}) ({and} 10... Na6 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nb4 13. Qe2 Nd3 {The Nd3 is strong but very unstable.} (13... O-O {transposes to 10... 0-0.}) 14. Rab1 $146 ({The previously played} 14. b3 {Gelfand,B - Sarana,A Moscow 2020 should be met with} Qa5 $1 $146 15. Nd1 Qb4 16. bxc4 Qxc4 $132 {I am not sure if White has more than full compensation for the pawn.}) 14... O-O ({In case of} 14... Qa5 {, White has a powerful tactical resource:} 15. b4 $1 Qa6 16. e5 Nf5 17. Qa2 $36 {The poor Qa6 makes Black's position very difficult.}) 15. b3 Qa5 16. Na2 $1 {An excellent move. The Na2 is controlling many squares.} e5 (16... cxb3 17. Rxb3 $18) 17. bxc4 Qxa4 18. Rfd1 $36 {The vulnerability of a few of Black's pieces makes the situation critical for him.}) 11. Qe2 O-O 12. Rad1 {The last preparations before active actions.} Na6 13. h3 $1 {White sacrifices the second pawn to get rid of the nasty pin.} Bxf3 ({After} 13... Bxh3 14. Bxh3 Qxh3 15. e5 $1 {Black is forced to retreat his knight and disconnect his rooks.} Ne8 ({Bad is} 15... Nf5 $2 16. Ng5 Qh6 17. Bc1 $18 {Black loses because of the poorly placed queen on h6.}) 16. d5 $1 {There is no need to waste a tempo on taking the c4-pawn - it is more important to open the d-file.} Nec7 17. dxc6 bxc6 18. Qxc4 {The activity of White's pieces and the poor Na6 provide White with more than full compensation.}) 14. Bxf3 Nb4 {This position took place in Stukan,M - Basso,P Novi Sad 2021. My new but natural idea is} 15. Bg5 $1 $146 {It turns out that Black has no comfortable way of defending the pawn.} e5 {This move is connected with an exchange sacrifice.} ({The alternatives are inferior:} 15... Qd7 $6 16. e5 Nc8 17. Qxc4 a5 18. Bg4 $16 {Black's position is tightly squeezed.}) ({The same can be said about} 15... f6 $6 16. Bg4 Qd8 17. Be6+ Kh8 18. Be3 $16) 16. Be7 Qc7 17. Bxf8 Rxf8 18. d5 $14 {Black's compensation is insufficient.} *

